57259079}} }}</ref> \"The goal is God--not going straight. Straight people don't go to Heaven, redeemed people do.\" \n\nDuring Rogers' involvement in the mid to late 1980s, Exodus International had offices on five continents and declared that \"all homosexual relationships are sinful.\"<ref name=\"RussellHomosexuals\">{{cite news |last1=Russell |first1=Candice |title=GOING STRAIGHT DOCUMENTARY FOCUSES ON EFFORTS TO 'CURE' HOMOSEXUALS |publisher=Sun Sentinel |date=14 June 1994|id={{ProQuest|388682062}} }}</ref> In conducting a speaking tour in 2008 Rogers\u2019 message included, \"Homosexuality is out of tune with religion; it is not what God planned for human sexuality.\" <ref name=\"MaraghyDenial\" /><ref name=\"PollardInvestigation\">{{cite news |last1=Pollard |first1=Ruth |title=God's cure for gays lost in sin: FACING THEIR DEMONS - A HERALD INVESTIGATION |publisher=Sydney Morning Herald |date=19 March 2008|id={{ProQuest|364377547}} }}</ref><ref>{{cite web|author=Bruce, Clara.|url=https://hope1032.com.au/stories/faith/christian-living/2017/sy-rogers-message-grace-sexual-brokenness-colour-conference/|title=Sy Rogers' Message of Grace for Sexual Brokenness, at Colour Conference |website=[[Hope 103.2]] |date=2017-03-01 |accessdate=2019-02-28}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.stuff.co.nz/southland-times/news/10289301/Youths-flock-to-Queenstown-for-conference|title=Youths flock to Queenstown for conference |website=Southland Times |date=2014-07-21 |accessdate=2019-03-04}}</ref><ref name=\"PollardInvestigation\" /> Writing in [[The Gay & Lesbian Review Worldwide]], gay rights advocate [[Wayne Besen]] argued that during the AIDS epidemic \"some men were literally scared straight - or at least into making the futile attempt,\" bringing a degree of momentary success to Exodus International.<ref name=\"BesenMovement\">{{cite journal |last1=Besen |first1=Wayne |title=The Politics of the Ex-Gay Movement |journal=The Gay & Lesbian Review Worldwide |date=July 2007 |volume=14 |issue=4 |id={{ProQuest|198678084}} }}</ref> In 2016, ''[[The Daily Beast]]'' reported that Rogers's ministry had moved away from the ex-gay message many years earlier.<ref name=\"TDB\">{{cite web|url=http://www.thedailybeast.com/articles/2016/01/17/sex-abuse-gay-conversion-therapy-the-dark-past-of-justin-bieber-s-megachurch-hillsong.html|title=Sex Abuse & Gay Conversion Therapy: The Dark Past of Justin Bieber's Megachurch Hillsong|author=Zadrozny, Brandy|date=January 16, 2016|work=[[The Daily Beast]]}}</ref>\n\nRogers is portrayed in the 1993 documentary ''[[One Nation Under God (1993 film)|One Nation Under God]]''.<ref name=\"RussellHomosexuals\"/><ref name=\"BesenMovement\"/><ref name=\"SinclairStudents\">{{cite news |last1=Sinclair |first1=Harriet |title=U.S.'s Richest Boarding School Admits It Showed Anti-Gay Videos To Students |url=https://www.newsweek.com/countrys-richest-boarding-school-admits-it-showed-anti-gay-videos-students-634528 |accessdate=4 March 2019 |publisher=Newsweek |date=10 July 2017}}</ref>\n\nRogers and his wife Karen married in 1982 and had children and grandchildren.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://now.hillsongchannel.com/colour-conference-the-green-room/videos/hillsongchannel-colour-conference-the-green-room-s3-e7-mezzanine|title=Sy & Karen Rogers|website=Hillsong Channel NOW|language=en|access-date=2019-04-03}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://syrogers.com/speaking/sy-bio/|title=Sy Bio {{!}} Sy Rogers|language=en-US|access-date=2019-04-03}}</ref> From 2012, he was a Teaching Pastor with the multi-campus LIFE Church & College in Auckland, New Zealand.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.rhema.co.nz/shows-djs/interviews/item/178-sy-rodgers-chats-with-andrew|title=Sy Rogers chats with Andrew|last=Ashcroft|first=Nerida|website=www.rhema.co.nz|language=en-gb|access-date=2019-04-03}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://thelifechurch.com/posts/guest-speaker-sy-rogers|title=Guest Speaker: Sy Rogers|website=thelifechurch.com|access-date=2019-04-03}}</ref>\n\nOn 20 April 2020, Life Church NZ posted to Instagram that Rogers had died.<ref name=\"Life Church NZ on Instagram\">https://www.instagram.com/p/B_Mon-hgoJv/</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*{{imdb name|nm4937197}}\n* {{official|http://www.syrogers.com}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Rogers, Sy}}\n[[Category:American Christian clergy]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:American activists]]\n[[Category:Ex-gay movement]]\n[[Category:LGBT people from the United States]]\n[[Category:People who detransitioned]]\n[[Category:Year of birth missing (living people)]]\n{{authority control}}\n", "name_user": "NZealand01", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eReferences:Sy Rogers Date of Death Correction", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Sy_Rogers"}
{"title_page": "Nova Scotia killings", "text_new": "<noinclude>{{User:RMCD bot/subject notice|1=2020 Nova Scotia attacks|2=Talk:Nova Scotia killings#Requested move 20 April 2020 }}\n</noinclude>{{pp-move-dispute|small=yes}}\n{{short description|Series of killings in Nova Scotia, Canada}}\n{{Authority control}}\n{{Current|date=April 2020}}\n{{Use mdy dates|date=April 2020}}\n{{Use Canadian English|date=April 2020}}\n{{Infobox civilian attack\n| title            = Nova Scotia killings\n{{OSM Location map\n| coord            = {{coord|45.1965|-63.3377}}\n|  zoom            = 7\n| float            = center\n| width            = 300\n| height           = 206\n| caption          =\n|   title          =\n|    minimap       = file\n|  mini-file       = Canada location map.svg\n| mini-width       = 120\n|mini-height       = 64\n|  minipog-x       = 105\n|  minipog-y       = 48\n|  scalemark       = 120 <!-- shifts the scalemark further to the left -->\n|      shape1      = image\n|       mark1      = Red pog.svg\n|      label1      = Portapique, NS\n| mark-coord1      = {{coord|45.4015|-63.6977}}\n|  label-pos1      = bottom\n| label-size1      = 10\n|label-color1      = black\n| label-offset-x1  =\n| label-offset-y1  =\n|mark-title1       = [[Portapique, Nova Scotia]]\n|mark-image1       =\n|mark-description1 =\n\n|      label2      = Wentworth, NS\n|       mark2      = Red pog.svg\n| mark-size2       = 8\n|  label-pos2      = left\n| label-size2      = 10\n|label-color2      = black\n| mark-coord2      = {{coord|45.6564|-63.5493}}\n|mark-title2       = [[Wentworth, Nova Scotia]]\n\n|      label3      = Shubenacadie, NS\n|       mark3      = Red pog.svg\n| mark-size3       = 8\n|  label-pos3      = left\n| label-size3      = 10\n|label-color3      = black\n| mark-coord3      = {{coord|45.0879|-63.4019}}\n|mark-title3       = [[Shubenacadie, Nova Scotia]]\n\n|      label4      = Enfield, NS\n|       mark4      = Red pog.svg\n| mark-size4       = 8\n|  label-pos4      = left\n| label-size4      = 10\n|label-color4      = black\n| mark-coord4      = {{coord|44.9274|-63.5366}}\n|mark-title4       = [[Enfield, Nova Scotia]]\n}}\n| partof           = \n| image            = \n| image_size       = \n| alt              = \n| caption          = \n| map              = \n| map_size         = \n| map_alt          = \n| map_caption      = Portapique in Nova Scotia\n| susperp          = \n| location         = [[Nova Scotia]], Canada\n| target           = \n| date             = {{start date|2020|4|18}}\u2013{{end date|2020|4|19}}\n| time             = \n| timezone         = [[UTC\u221203:00]]\n| coordinates      = \n| type             = [[Spree killer|Spree shooting]], [[mass shooting]],<ref name=\"Vox\" /> [[arson]]\n| weapons          = Firearm(s)\n| fatalities       = At least 19 (including the perpetrator)<ref name=\"CBC3\"/>\n| injuries         = At least 2<ref name=\"CBC3\"/>\n| victim           = \n| perp             = Gabriel Wortman\n| numparts         = \n| numpart          = \n| dfens            = \n| dfen             = \n| footage          = \n| motive           = Under investigation\n}}\n\nOn April 18 and April 19, 2020, Gabriel Wortman killed at least 18 people and set fire to at least five buildings in the [[Canadian province]] of [[Nova Scotia]] before being killed by the police following a vehicle pursuit.<ref name=\"CBC4\">{{cite news|url=https://www.cbc.ca/news/canada/nova-scotia/mass-killing-shooting-victims-remembered-1.5538032|title=Teacher, family of 3 and RCMP officer among victims of N.S. shooting rampage|publisher=CBC News|accessdate=April 20, 2020|date=April 19, 2020}}</ref>\n\nIt is the deadliest attack involving the use of firearms in Canadian history, surpassing the 1989 [[\u00c9cole Polytechnique massacre]], during which 15 people were killed.<ref name=\"AP\">{{cite news|url=https://apnews.com/7c9a33ae52420e0ddbfb5275898a7e79|title=16 killed in shooting rampage, deadliest in Canadian history|last=Gillies|first=Rob|publisher=Associated Press|accessdate=April 19, 2020|date=April 19, 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200419202425/https://apnews.com/7c9a33ae52420e0ddbfb5275898a7e79|archive-date=April 19, 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> Police say the motive has not yet been established.<ref name=\"nyt-nova-scotia-shooting-gabriel-wortman\">{{Cite news|last=Diaz|first=Johnny|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2020/04/19/world/canada/nova-scotia-shooting-gabriel-wortman.html|title=Nova Scotia Shooting Kills at Least 16, Police Say|date=April 19, 2020|newspaper=[[The New York Times]]|access-date=April 19, 2020|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200419142013/https://www.nytimes.com/2020/04/19/world/canada/nova-scotia-shooting-gabriel-wortman.html|archive-date=April 19, 2020|last2=Bilefsky|first2=Dan}}</ref><ref name=\"Politico\">{{cite news|last=Blatchford|first=Andy|url=https://www.politico.com/news/2020/04/19/at-least-10-dead-in-canadian-shooting-rampage-195506|title=Gunman kills at least 16, including officer, in Nova Scotia|date=April 19, 2020|accessdate=April 20, 2020|publisher=Politico}}</ref>\n\n==Timeline==\nOn April 18, at around 11:00 p.m. [[Atlantic Time Zone|ADT]], [[Royal Canadian Mounted Police]] (RCMP) officers responded to multiple [[9-1-1]] calls regarding a gun-related incident in the community of [[Portapique]], {{convert|130|km|mi}} north of [[Halifax, Nova Scotia|Halifax]].<ref name=\"CBC3\">{{cite news|url=https://www.cbc.ca/news/canada/nova-scotia/mass-killings-what-we-know-what-we-don-t-1.5537918|title=Nova Scotia mass killings: What we know and what we don't know|date=April 19, 2020|accessdate=April 19, 2020|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200420034520/https://www.cbc.ca/news/canada/nova-scotia/mass-killings-what-we-know-what-we-don-t-1.5537918|archive-date=April 20, 2020|publisher=CBC News}}</ref><ref name=\"nyt-nova-scotia-shooting-gabriel-wortman\" /><ref name=\"CBC2\">{{cite news|url=https://www.cbc.ca/news/canada/nova-scotia/nova-scotia-timeline-active-shooter-portapique-1.5537756|title=Timeline: How an active-shooter situation unfolded in Nova Scotia|date=April 19, 2020|accessdate=April 19, 2020|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200420001136/https://www.cbc.ca/news/canada/nova-scotia/nova-scotia-timeline-active-shooter-portapique-1.5537756|archive-date=April 20, 2020|publisher=CBC News}}</ref><ref name=\"NBC\">{{cite news|last1=Madani|first1=Doha|url=https://www.nbcnews.com/news/world/canadian-authorities-say-mass-shooting-suspect-may-have-been-disguised-n1187381|title=16 dead, including officer, in shooting, Canadian authorities say|date=April 19, 2020|accessdate=April 19, 2020|publisher=NBC News|last2=Stelloh|first2=Tim}}</ref> Three houses on Portapique Beach Road were found on fire, and at least five victims were located; they were \"gunned down as they tried to escape the flames.\" One of the first officers to respond to the scene reported by radio that they had yet to locate an armed suspect, and that \"it's very bad what's going on down here.\"<ref name=\":2\">{{Cite news|last=Tasker|first=John Paul|url=https://www.cbc.ca/news/politics/nova-scotia-tick-tock-murder-rampage-1.5539000|title='Those scars will never heal': piecing together a gunman's murderous rampage in Nova Scotia|date=April 20, 2020|work=CBC News|access-date=April 21, 2020|url-status=live}}</ref><ref name=\"ABC\">{{cite news|last=Deliso|first=Meredith|url=https://abcnews.go.com/International/multiple-victims-canada-shooting-suspect-dressed-police-officer/story?id=70232582|title=16 dead, including police officer, in deadliest shooting in Canadian history|date=April 19, 2020|accessdate=April 19, 2020|publisher=ABC News}}</ref>\n\nAt 11:32 p.m., the RCMP sent a [[Twitter|tweet]] asking residents of the area to stay inside with their doors locked, but no message was sent through the provincial [[Emergency Alert System|emergency alert system]]. The investigation developed overnight, and by the morning of April 19, police said they were dealing with an [[active shooter]] situation.<ref name=\"CBC3\" /><ref name=\"nyt-nova-scotia-shooting-gabriel-wortman\" /><ref name=\"CBC2\" /><ref name=\"MassLive\">{{cite news|url=https://www.masslive.com/news/2020/04/nova-scotia-shooting-gabriel-wortman-kills-16-including-police-officer-in-canadas-deadliest-shooting-attack.html|title=Nova Scotia shooting: Gabriel Wortman kills 16 including police officer in Canada's deadliest shooting attack|date=April 19, 2020|accessdate=April 19, 2020|publisher=MassLive}}</ref>\n\nAt around 8:00 a.m., a 9-1-1 caller reported \"an explosion and gunfire\" at a house on Hunter Road in [[Wentworth, Nova Scotia|Wentworth]], approximately {{convert|37|km|mi}} north of Portapique. The two residents were killed, as was a neighbour who went to render assistance. Another victim was then allegedly shot and killed while walking in the community of [[Wentworth Valley]], on the road back south to Portapique.<ref name=\"CBC4\" />\n\nRCMP identified Wortman, age 51, as the suspect at 8:54 a.m., and warned that he was [[Police impersonation|dressed as an RCMP officer and operating a replica police vehicle]].<ref name=\"CBC2\" /><ref name=\"CTV\">{{cite news|last=Jerrett|first=Andrea|url=https://atlantic.ctvnews.ca/nova-scotia-shooting-suspect-shot-and-killed-by-police-1.4902687|title=At least 18 people killed in N.S. shooting; deadliest such attack in Canada: police|date=April 19, 2020|accessdate=April 19, 2020|publisher=CTV News}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|last=Shah|first=Maryam|url=https://globalnews.ca/news/6840120/nova-scotia-shooting-timeline/|title=Timeline: What we know about the Nova Scotia shooting spree|date=April 19, 2020|accessdate=April 19, 2020|publisher=Global News}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.ctvnews.ca/canada/a-timeline-of-the-deadly-shooting-incident-in-nova-scotia-1.4902954|title=A timeline of the deadly shooting incident in Nova Scotia|last1=Neustaeter|first1=Brooklyn|last2=Lopez-Martinez|first2=Melissa|date=April 19, 2020|website=CTV News|language=en|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200420053707/https://www.ctvnews.ca/canada/a-timeline-of-the-deadly-shooting-incident-in-nova-scotia-1.4902954|archive-date=April 20, 2020|access-date=April 19, 2020}}</ref><ref name=\"CBC\">{{cite news|url=https://www.cbc.ca/news/canada/nova-scotia/rcmp-weapon-lockdown-portapique-1.5537598|title=RCMP officer among the dead after Nova Scotia gunman's rampage|date=April 19, 2020|accessdate=April 19, 2020|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200419130936/https://www.cbc.ca/news/canada/nova-scotia/rcmp-weapon-lockdown-portapique-1.5537598|archive-date=April 19, 2020|publisher=CBC News}}</ref> Between 10:04 and 11:04 a.m., he was sighted in or near the communities of [[Glenholme]], [[Debert]], and [[Brookfield, Nova Scotia|Brookfield]], indicating he was travelling south along [[Nova Scotia Highway 102|Highway 102]] toward Halifax.<ref name=\":2\" /> A law enforcement source told [[CNN]] that during this time, Wortman began randomly pulling drivers over and killing them.<ref name=\"CNN\" />\n\nSometime shortly before 11:24 a.m., Wortman encountered RCMP Constable Heidi Stevenson along [[Nova Scotia Trunk 2|Highway 2]], in the community of [[Shubenacadie, Nova Scotia|Shubenacadie]]. Witnesses reported seeing Wortman run towards Stevenson and hearing an exchange of gunfire, which killed Stevenson and injured another officer.<ref name=\"CBC\" /> Two burning cars were observed at the scene, including an RCMP cruiser which may have been Wortman's replica.<ref name=\"CBC6\">{{cite news|url=https://www.cbc.ca/news/canada/nova-scotia/mass-killings-shooting-community-reaction-1.5538181|title=Death toll from Nova Scotia gunman's rampage climbs to 19|date=April 20, 2020|accessdate=April 20, 2020|publisher=CBC News}}</ref> Thereafter, he continued south in a silver [[Chevrolet Tracker (Americas)|Chevrolet Tracker]] [[Sport utility vehicle|SUV]] stolen from one of his victims, and he was next seen in [[Milford (Halifax), Nova Scotia|Milford]].<ref name=\"CBC2\" /><ref name=\"BBC\">{{cite news|url=https://www.bbc.com/news/world-us-canada-52346447|title=Canada shooting: Gunman kills at least 18 in Nova Scotia|date=April 19, 2020|accessdate=April 19, 2020|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200419211041/https://www.bbc.com/news/world-us-canada-52346447|archive-date=April 19, 2020|publisher=BBC News}}</ref>\n\nFinally, at 11:40 a.m., over 12 hours after police responded to the first firearms complaint, Wortman was shot and killed by police at the [[Irving Oil|Irving]] Big Stop gas station in [[Enfield, Nova Scotia|Enfield]], about {{convert|92|km|mi}} south of Portapique and about {{convert|40|km|mi}} north of Halifax.<ref name=\"Vox\">{{cite news|last=Collins|first=Sean|url=https://www.vox.com/world/2020/4/19/21227349/mass-shooting-nova-scotia-canada-enfield-portapique|title=What we know about a mass shooting in Nova Scotia, Canada|date=April 19, 2020|accessdate=April 19, 2020|publisher=Vox}}</ref><ref name=\"CBC2\" /><ref name=\"CTV\" />\n\n==Investigation==\nNo motive has been established for the killings, although they are not considered by police to be an act of [[terrorism in Canada|terrorism]].<ref name=\"nyt-nova-scotia-shooting-gabriel-wortman\" />\n\nOn the afternoon of April 20, RCMP Chief Superintendent Chris Leather said there were 16 crime scenes in total, including five structure fires, which were scattered over a distance of at least {{convert|50|km|mi}}. He said he expected the death toll to rise as these crime scenes are investigated further.<ref name=\"CBC6\" />\n\nCiting an unnamed law enforcement source, CNN reported that the incident may have begun as a case of domestic violence at one of the homes in Portapique, where Wortman was allegedly trying to find a former partner.<ref name=\"CNN\" />\n\n[[Nova Scotia]]'s [[Serious Incident Response Team]] (SIRT) announced it would conduct an investigation into the officer-involved shooting, as well as a second police use-of-force incident.<ref name=\"CBC\" /><ref name=\"CBC6\" /><ref>{{cite web|url=https://sirt.novascotia.ca/investigation-begins-enfield-death|title=INVESTIGATION BEGINS INTO ENFIELD DEATH|publisher=Serious Incident Response Team|date=April 19, 2020|accessdate=April 20, 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://sirt.novascotia.ca/sirt-investigate-discharge-firearm-rcmp-officers|title=SIRT TO INVESTIGATE DISCHARGE OF FIREARM BY RCMP OFFICERS|publisher=Serious Incident Response Team|date=April 20, 2020|accessdate=April 20, 2020}}</ref>\n\nQuestions were raised about why Nova Scotia did not use its [[emergency alert system]] to warn the public about the killings. The RCMP used Twitter to provide updates, but the areas affected had poor Internet service and were mostly populated by seniors who might not use social media. Usage of Nova Scotia's emergency alert system would have sent text messages advising residents of what was happening and to stay indoors. Superintendent Leather said an investigation would be conducted into the decision-making process to alert the public.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.cbc.ca/news/canada/nova-scotia/ns-public-alert-1.5538286|title=N.S. premier not ready to question if a public alert should have been issued about gunman|publisher=CBC News|last=Gorman|first=Michael|date=April 20, 2020|accessdate=April 20, 2020}}</ref>\n\n==Victims==\nWortman killed at least 18 people, one of them RCMP Constable Heidi Stevenson, a 23-year veteran. He shot and wounded a second RCMP officer, who is in stable condition.<ref name=\"CBC3\"/><ref name=\"CBC\" /><ref name=\"global-news-rcmp-active-shooter-portapique-n-s\">{{Cite news|last=Quon|first=Alexander|url=https://globalnews.ca/news/6838880/rcmp-active-shooter-portapique-n-s/|title=17 dead, including one RCMP officer, after shooting spree in Portapique, N.S.|date=April 19, 2020|access-date=April 19, 2020|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200419202613/https://globalnews.ca/news/6838880/rcmp-active-shooter-portapique-n-s/|archive-date=April 19, 2020|publisher=[[Global News]]|last2=Stephenson|first2=Mercedes}}</ref> At least one other person was injured.<ref name=\"CBC3\" /> According to Commissioner [[Brenda Lucki]], some of his first victims were closely connected to him, but as he continued, his targets became more random.<ref name=\"nyt-nova-scotia-shooting-gabriel-wortman\" /> The dead are believed to have died from gunshot wounds, but other causes are also being investigated.<ref name=\"CBC3\" /><ref name=\"BBC\" /> The RCMP expects to find more bodies within the remnants of five structure fires.<ref name=\"CTV4\">{{cite web|url=https://www.ctvnews.ca/canada/nova-scotia-rampage-results-in-18-victims-16-crime-scenes-1.4903398|title=Nova Scotia rampage results in 18 victims, 16 crime scenes|date=April 20, 2020|work=[[CTV News]]|first=Meredith|last=MacLeod|accessdate=April 20, 2020}}</ref>\n\n==Perpetrator==\nThe RCMP identified the perpetrator as Gabriel Wortman, a [[denturist]] working in the Halifax area. He owned real estate in Portapique and [[Dartmouth, Nova Scotia|Dartmouth]].<ref name=\"CBC\"/><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.theguardian.com/world/2020/apr/20/nova-scotia-shooting-gunman-profile-quiet-gentle-denturist|title=Nova Scotia shooting: shock and surprise at killings by denturist|first=Leyland|last=Cecco|date=April 19, 2020|accessdate=April 19, 2020|website=The Guardian}}</ref> He attended [[Riverview High School (New Brunswick)|Riverview High School]] in New Brunswick and aspired to be a police officer.<ref name=\":1\">{{Cite web|url=https://atlantic.ctvnews.ca/just-unbelievable-neighbours-of-nova-scotia-shooting-suspect-shocked-by-news-1.4903021|title='Just unbelievable': Neighbours of Nova Scotia shooting suspect shocked by news|date=April 19, 2020|website=CTV News|language=en|access-date=April 20, 2020}}</ref> Acquaintances described him as a house-proud and polite man who often spent time at a seasonal home near [[Cobequid Bay]].<ref name=\"CTV5\">{{cite news|url=https://www.ctvnews.ca/canada/what-we-know-about-the-nova-scotia-rampage-suspect-1.4903920|title=What we know about the Nova Scotia rampage suspect|publisher=CTV News|last=Bogart|first=Nicole|date=April 20, 2020|accessdate=April 20, 2020}}</ref>\n\nWortman had a hobby of buying law enforcement memorabilia and refurbishing old police cruisers. One person called his home a \"shrine\" for the RCMP.<ref name=\":0\">{{cite news|url=https://www.theglobeandmail.com/canada/article-nova-scotia-mass-shooter-was-a-denturist-with-an-obsession-for/|title=Nova Scotia mass shooter was a denturist with an obsession for policing|publisher=The Globe and Mail|last1=Woo|first1=Andrew|last2=Mercer|first2=Greg|date=April 19, 2020|accessdate=April 20, 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200420055810/https://www.theglobeandmail.com/canada/article-nova-scotia-mass-shooter-was-a-denturist-with-an-obsession-for/|archive-date=April 20, 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> He stored the two old police cruisers that he bought behind his dental clinic.<ref name=\":1\" /><ref name=\"CTV5\" />\n\nNeighbours said Wortman struggled with [[alcohol use]] and his profitable business was impacted by the [[2020 coronavirus pandemic in Nova Scotia|coronavirus pandemic]], which forced all non-essential dental services to cease.<ref name=\":0\" />\n\n==Reactions==\n[[Nova Scotia Premier]] [[Stephen McNeil]] told reporters, \"This is one of the most senseless acts of violence in our province's history.\" He expressed his condolences to the residents affected and the families of the victims.<ref name=\"CTV2\">{{cite news|url=https://atlantic.ctvnews.ca/shooting-one-of-the-most-senseless-acts-of-violence-in-nova-scotia-s-history-premier-1.4902917|title=Shooting 'one of the most senseless acts of violence' in Nova Scotia's history: premier|last=Jerrett|first=Andrea|publisher=CTV News|accessdate=April 19, 2020|date=April 19, 2020}}</ref> Prime Minister [[Justin Trudeau]] also expressed his condolences.<ref name=\"CBC\" /> During his morning address from [[Rideau Cottage]] on April 20, he reaffirmed his commitment to strengthening gun control.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.ctvnews.ca/politics/trudeau-reiterates-gun-control-commitment-in-wake-of-mass-shooting-1.4903966|title=Trudeau reiterates gun control commitment in wake of mass shooting|publisher=CTV News|last=Gilmore|first=Rachel|date=April 20, 2020|accessdate=April 20, 2020}}</ref> Flags across Canada were lowered to [[half-mast]],<ref name=\"Guardian2\">{{cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/world/2020/apr/20/nova-scotia-shooting-friends-family-pay-tribute-victims|title=Nova Scotia shooting: friends and family pay tribute to 'beautiful souls' lost in rampage|publisher=The Guardian|last=Cecco|first=Leyland|date=April 20, 2020|accessdate=April 20, 2020}}</ref> and the [[House of Commons of Canada|House of Commons]] observed a moment of silence for the victims.<ref>{{cite web| url=https://www.cbc.ca/news/politics/trudeau-nova-scotia-shooting-1.5538301| title='We're going to get through this together': Trudeau calls for unity after mass killing| website=CBC News| date=April 20, 2020| accessdate=April 20, 2020| url-status=live| archive-url=http://archive.is/7qFSQ| archive-date=April 20, 2020}}</ref>\n\nThe [[White House]] released a statement that condemned the killings and expressed US President [[Donald Trump]] and US First Lady [[Melania Trump]]'s condolences.<ref name=\"CNN\">{{cite news|url=https://www.cnn.com/2020/04/20/americas/nova-scotia-shooting-monday/index.html|title=Gunman evaded police for nearly 12 hours and killed at least 18 in one of Canada's deadliest mass shootings|publisher=CNN|last1=McLaughlin|first1=Eliott C.|last2=Newton|first2=Paula|date=April 20, 2020|accessdate=April 20, 2020}}</ref>\n\n==See also==\n* [[Moncton shooting]]\n* [[List of massacres in Canada]]\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n[[Category:2020 crimes in Canada]]\n[[Category:2020 in Nova Scotia]]\n[[Category:2020 mass shootings]]\n[[Category:2020 mass shootings in North America]]\n[[Category:2020 murders in North America]]\n[[Category:2020s mass shootings in North America]]\n[[Category:21st-century mass murder in North America]]\n[[Category:April 2020 crimes]]\n[[Category:April 2020 events in Canada]]\n[[Category:Arson in Canada]]\n[[Category:Arson in the 2020s]]\n[[Category:Attacks in 2020]]\n[[Category:Crime in Nova Scotia]]\n[[Category:Death in Nova Scotia]]\n[[Category:Deaths by firearm in Canada]]\n[[Category:Mass shootings in Canada]]\n[[Category:Mass murder in Canada]]\n[[Category:Royal Canadian Mounted Police]]\n[[Category:Spree shootings in Canada]]\n", "text_old": "<noinclude>{{User:RMCD bot/subject notice|1=2020 Nova Scotia attacks|2=Talk:Nova Scotia killings#Requested move 20 April 2020 }}\n</noinclude>{{pp-move-dispute|small=yes}}\n{{short description|Series of killings in Nova Scotia, Canada}}\n{{Authority control}}\n{{Current|date=April 2020}}\n{{Use mdy dates|date=April 2020}}\n{{Use Canadian English|date=April 2020}}\n{{Infobox civilian attack\n| title            = Nova Scotia killings\n{{OSM Location map\n| coord            = {{coord|45.1965|-63.3377}}\n|  zoom            = 7\n| float            = center\n| width            = 300\n| height           = 206\n| caption          =\n|   title          =\n|    minimap       = file\n|  mini-file       = Canada location map.svg\n| mini-width       = 120\n|mini-height       = 64\n|  minipog-x       = 105\n|  minipog-y       = 48\n|  scalemark       = 120 <!-- shifts the scalemark further to the left -->\n|      shape1      = image\n|       mark1      = Red pog.svg\n|      label1      = Portapique, NS\n| mark-coord1      = {{coord|45.4015|-63.6977}}\n|  label-pos1      = bottom\n| label-size1      = 10\n|label-color1      = black\n| label-offset-x1  =\n| label-offset-y1  =\n|mark-title1       = [[Portapique, Nova Scotia]]\n|mark-image1       =\n|mark-description1 =\n\n|      label2      = Wentworth, NS\n|       mark2      = Red pog.svg\n| mark-size2       = 8\n|  label-pos2      = left\n| label-size2      = 10\n|label-color2      = black\n| mark-coord2      = {{coord|45.6564|-63.5493}}\n|mark-title2       = [[Wentworth, Nova Scotia]]\n\n|      label3      = Shubenacadie, NS\n|       mark3      = Red pog.svg\n| mark-size3       = 8\n|  label-pos3      = left\n| label-size3      = 10\n|label-color3      = black\n| mark-coord3      = {{coord|45.0879|-63.4019}}\n|mark-title3       = [[Shubenacadie, Nova Scotia]]\n\n|      label4      = Enfield, NS\n|       mark4      = Red pog.svg\n| mark-size4       = 8\n|  label-pos4      = left\n| label-size4      = 10\n|label-color4      = black\n| mark-coord4      = {{coord|44.9274|-63.5366}}\n|mark-title4       = [[Enfield, Nova Scotia]]\n}}\n| partof           = \n| image            = \n| image_size       = \n| alt              = \n| caption          = \n| map              = \n| map_size         = \n| map_alt          = \n| map_caption      = Portapique in Nova Scotia\n| susperp          = \n| location         = [[Nova Scotia]], Canada\n| target           = \n| date             = {{start date|2020|4|18}}\u2013{{end date|2020|4|19}}\n| time             = \n| timezone         = [[UTC\u221203:00]]\n| coordinates      = \n| type             = [[Spree killer|Spree shooting]], [[mass shooting]],<ref name=\"Vox\" /> [[arson]]\n| weapons          = Firearm(s)\n| fatalities       = At least 19 (including the perpetrator)<ref name=\"CBC3\"/>\n| injuries         = At least 2<ref name=\"CBC3\"/>\n| victim           = \n| perp             = Gabriel Wortman\n| numparts         = \n| numpart          = \n| dfens            = \n| dfen             = \n| footage          = \n| motive           = Under investigation\n}}\n\nOn April 18 and April 19, 2020, Gabriel Wortman killed at least 18 people and set fire to at least five buildings in the [[Canadian province]] of [[Nova Scotia]] before being killed by the police following a vehicle pursuit.<ref name=\"CBC4\">{{cite news|url=https://www.cbc.ca/news/canada/nova-scotia/mass-killing-shooting-victims-remembered-1.5538032|title=Teacher, family of 3 and RCMP officer among victims of N.S. shooting rampage|publisher=CBC News|accessdate=April 20, 2020|date=April 19, 2020}}</ref>\n\nIt is the deadliest attack involving the use of firearms in Canadian history, surpassing the 1989 [[\u00c9cole Polytechnique massacre]], during which 15 people were killed.<ref name=\"AP\">{{cite news|url=https://apnews.com/7c9a33ae52420e0ddbfb5275898a7e79|title=16 killed in shooting rampage, deadliest in Canadian history|last=Gillies|first=Rob|publisher=Associated Press|accessdate=April 19, 2020|date=April 19, 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200419202425/https://apnews.com/7c9a33ae52420e0ddbfb5275898a7e79|archive-date=April 19, 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> Police say the motive has not yet been established.<ref name=\"nyt-nova-scotia-shooting-gabriel-wortman\">{{Cite news|last=Diaz|first=Johnny|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2020/04/19/world/canada/nova-scotia-shooting-gabriel-wortman.html|title=Nova Scotia Shooting Kills at Least 16, Police Say|date=April 19, 2020|newspaper=[[The New York Times]]|access-date=April 19, 2020|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200419142013/https://www.nytimes.com/2020/04/19/world/canada/nova-scotia-shooting-gabriel-wortman.html|archive-date=April 19, 2020|last2=Bilefsky|first2=Dan}}</ref><ref name=\"Politico\">{{cite news|last=Blatchford|first=Andy|url=https://www.politico.com/news/2020/04/19/at-least-10-dead-in-canadian-shooting-rampage-195506|title=Gunman kills at least 16, including officer, in Nova Scotia|date=April 19, 2020|accessdate=April 20, 2020|publisher=Politico}}</ref>\n\n==Timeline==\nOn April 18, at around 11:00 p.m. [[Atlantic Time Zone|ADT]], [[Royal Canadian Mounted Police]] (RCMP) officers responded to multiple [[9-1-1]] calls regarding a gun-related incident in the community of [[Portapique]], {{convert|130|km|mi}} north of [[Halifax, Nova Scotia|Halifax]].<ref name=\"CBC3\">{{cite news|url=https://www.cbc.ca/news/canada/nova-scotia/mass-killings-what-we-know-what-we-don-t-1.5537918|title=Nova Scotia mass killings: What we know and what we don't know|date=April 19, 2020|accessdate=April 19, 2020|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200420034520/https://www.cbc.ca/news/canada/nova-scotia/mass-killings-what-we-know-what-we-don-t-1.5537918|archive-date=April 20, 2020|publisher=CBC News}}</ref><ref name=\"nyt-nova-scotia-shooting-gabriel-wortman\" /><ref name=\"CBC2\">{{cite news|url=https://www.cbc.ca/news/canada/nova-scotia/nova-scotia-timeline-active-shooter-portapique-1.5537756|title=Timeline: How an active-shooter situation unfolded in Nova Scotia|date=April 19, 2020|accessdate=April 19, 2020|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200420001136/https://www.cbc.ca/news/canada/nova-scotia/nova-scotia-timeline-active-shooter-portapique-1.5537756|archive-date=April 20, 2020|publisher=CBC News}}</ref><ref name=\"NBC\">{{cite news|last1=Madani|first1=Doha|url=https://www.nbcnews.com/news/world/canadian-authorities-say-mass-shooting-suspect-may-have-been-disguised-n1187381|title=16 dead, including officer, in shooting, Canadian authorities say|date=April 19, 2020|accessdate=April 19, 2020|publisher=NBC News|last2=Stelloh|first2=Tim}}</ref> Three houses on Portapique Beach Road were found on fire, and at least five victims were located; they were \"gunned down as they tried to escape the flames.\" One of the first officers to respond to the scene reported by radio that they had yet to locate an armed suspect, and that \"it's very bad what's going on down here.\"<ref name=\":2\">{{Cite news|last=Tasker|first=John Paul|url=https://www.cbc.ca/news/politics/nova-scotia-tick-tock-murder-rampage-1.5539000|title='Those scars will never heal': piecing together a gunman's murderous rampage in Nova Scotia|date=April 20, 2020|work=CBC News|access-date=April 21, 2020|url-status=live}}</ref><ref name=\"ABC\">{{cite news|last=Deliso|first=Meredith|url=https://abcnews.go.com/International/multiple-victims-canada-shooting-suspect-dressed-police-officer/story?id=70232582|title=16 dead, including police officer, in deadliest shooting in Canadian history|date=April 19, 2020|accessdate=April 19, 2020|publisher=ABC News}}</ref>\n\nAt 11:32 p.m., the RCMP sent a [[Twitter|tweet]] asking residents of the area to stay inside with their doors locked, but no message was sent through the provincial [[Emergency Alert System|emergency alert system]]. The investigation developed overnight, and by the morning of April 19, police said they were dealing with an [[active shooter]] situation.<ref name=\"CBC3\" /><ref name=\"nyt-nova-scotia-shooting-gabriel-wortman\" /><ref name=\"CBC2\" /><ref name=\"MassLive\">{{cite news|url=https://www.masslive.com/news/2020/04/nova-scotia-shooting-gabriel-wortman-kills-16-including-police-officer-in-canadas-deadliest-shooting-attack.html|title=Nova Scotia shooting: Gabriel Wortman kills 16 including police officer in Canada's deadliest shooting attack|date=April 19, 2020|accessdate=April 19, 2020|publisher=MassLive}}</ref>\n\nAt around 8:00 a.m., a 9-1-1 caller reported \"an explosion and gunfire\" at a house on Hunter Road in [[Wentworth, Nova Scotia|Wentworth]], approximately {{convert|37|km|mi}} north of Portapique. The two residents were killed, as was a neighbour who went to render assistance. Another victim was then allegedly shot and killed while walking in the community of [[Wentworth Valley]], on the road back south to Portapique.<ref name=\"CBC4\" />\n\nRCMP identified Wortman, age 51, as the suspect at 8:54 a.m., and warned that he was [[Police impersonation|dressed as an RCMP officer and operating a replica police vehicle]].<ref name=\"CBC2\" /><ref name=\"CTV\">{{cite news|last=Jerrett|first=Andrea|url=https://atlantic.ctvnews.ca/nova-scotia-shooting-suspect-shot-and-killed-by-police-1.4902687|title=At least 18 people killed in N.S. shooting; deadliest such attack in Canada: police|date=April 19, 2020|accessdate=April 19, 2020|publisher=CTV News}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|last=Shah|first=Maryam|url=https://globalnews.ca/news/6840120/nova-scotia-shooting-timeline/|title=Timeline: What we know about the Nova Scotia shooting spree|date=April 19, 2020|accessdate=April 19, 2020|publisher=Global News}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.ctvnews.ca/canada/a-timeline-of-the-deadly-shooting-incident-in-nova-scotia-1.4902954|title=A timeline of the deadly shooting incident in Nova Scotia|last1=Neustaeter|first1=Brooklyn|last2=Lopez-Martinez|first2=Melissa|date=April 19, 2020|website=CTV News|language=en|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200420053707/https://www.ctvnews.ca/canada/a-timeline-of-the-deadly-shooting-incident-in-nova-scotia-1.4902954|archive-date=April 20, 2020|access-date=April 19, 2020}}</ref><ref name=\"CBC\">{{cite news|url=https://www.cbc.ca/news/canada/nova-scotia/rcmp-weapon-lockdown-portapique-1.5537598|title=RCMP officer among the dead after Nova Scotia gunman's rampage|date=April 19, 2020|accessdate=April 19, 2020|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200419130936/https://www.cbc.ca/news/canada/nova-scotia/rcmp-weapon-lockdown-portapique-1.5537598|archive-date=April 19, 2020|publisher=CBC News}}</ref> Between 10:04 and 11:04 a.m., he was sighted in or near the communities of [[Glenholme]], [[Debert]], and [[Brookfield, Nova Scotia|Brookfield]], indicating he was travelling south along [[Nova Scotia Highway 102|Highway 102]] toward Halifax.<ref name=\":2\" /> A law enforcement source told [[CNN]] that during this time, Wortman began randomly pulling people over and killing them.<ref name=\"CNN\" />\n\nSometime shortly before 11:24 a.m., Wortman encountered RCMP Constable Heidi Stevenson along [[Nova Scotia Trunk 2|Highway 2]], in the community of [[Shubenacadie, Nova Scotia|Shubenacadie]]. Witnesses reported seeing Wortman run towards Stevenson and hearing an exchange of gunfire, which killed Stevenson and injured another officer.<ref name=\"CBC\" /> Two burning cars were observed at the scene, including an RCMP cruiser which may have been Wortman's replica.<ref name=\"CBC6\">{{cite news|url=https://www.cbc.ca/news/canada/nova-scotia/mass-killings-shooting-community-reaction-1.5538181|title=Death toll from Nova Scotia gunman's rampage climbs to 19|date=April 20, 2020|accessdate=April 20, 2020|publisher=CBC News}}</ref> Thereafter, he continued south in a silver [[Chevrolet Tracker (Americas)|Chevrolet Tracker]] [[Sport utility vehicle|SUV]] stolen from one of his victims, and he was next seen in [[Milford (Halifax), Nova Scotia|Milford]].<ref name=\"CBC2\" /><ref name=\"BBC\">{{cite news|url=https://www.bbc.com/news/world-us-canada-52346447|title=Canada shooting: Gunman kills at least 18 in Nova Scotia|date=April 19, 2020|accessdate=April 19, 2020|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200419211041/https://www.bbc.com/news/world-us-canada-52346447|archive-date=April 19, 2020|publisher=BBC News}}</ref>\n\nFinally, at 11:40 a.m., over 12 hours after police responded to the first firearms complaint, Wortman was shot and killed by police at the [[Irving Oil|Irving]] Big Stop gas station in [[Enfield, Nova Scotia|Enfield]], about {{convert|92|km|mi}} south of Portapique and about {{convert|40|km|mi}} north of Halifax.<ref name=\"Vox\">{{cite news|last=Collins|first=Sean|url=https://www.vox.com/world/2020/4/19/21227349/mass-shooting-nova-scotia-canada-enfield-portapique|title=What we know about a mass shooting in Nova Scotia, Canada|date=April 19, 2020|accessdate=April 19, 2020|publisher=Vox}}</ref><ref name=\"CBC2\" /><ref name=\"CTV\" />\n\n==Investigation==\nNo motive has been established for the killings, although they are not considered by police to be an act of [[terrorism in Canada|terrorism]].<ref name=\"nyt-nova-scotia-shooting-gabriel-wortman\" />\n\nOn the afternoon of April 20, RCMP Chief Superintendent Chris Leather said there were 16 crime scenes in total, including five structure fires, which were scattered over a distance of at least {{convert|50|km|mi}}. He said he expected the death toll to rise as these crime scenes are investigated further.<ref name=\"CBC6\" />\n\nCiting an unnamed law enforcement source, CNN reported that the incident may have begun as a case of domestic violence at one of the homes in Portapique, where Wortman was allegedly trying to find a former partner.<ref name=\"CNN\" />\n\n[[Nova Scotia]]'s [[Serious Incident Response Team]] (SIRT) announced it would conduct an investigation into the officer-involved shooting, as well as a second police use-of-force incident.<ref name=\"CBC\" /><ref name=\"CBC6\" /><ref>{{cite web|url=https://sirt.novascotia.ca/investigation-begins-enfield-death|title=INVESTIGATION BEGINS INTO ENFIELD DEATH|publisher=Serious Incident Response Team|date=April 19, 2020|accessdate=April 20, 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://sirt.novascotia.ca/sirt-investigate-discharge-firearm-rcmp-officers|title=SIRT TO INVESTIGATE DISCHARGE OF FIREARM BY RCMP OFFICERS|publisher=Serious Incident Response Team|date=April 20, 2020|accessdate=April 20, 2020}}</ref>\n\nQuestions were raised about why Nova Scotia did not use its [[emergency alert system]] to warn the public about the killings. The RCMP used Twitter to provide updates, but the areas affected had poor Internet service and were mostly populated by seniors who might not use social media. Usage of Nova Scotia's emergency alert system would have sent text messages advising residents of what was happening and to stay indoors. Superintendent Leather said an investigation would be conducted into the decision-making process to alert the public.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.cbc.ca/news/canada/nova-scotia/ns-public-alert-1.5538286|title=N.S. premier not ready to question if a public alert should have been issued about gunman|publisher=CBC News|last=Gorman|first=Michael|date=April 20, 2020|accessdate=April 20, 2020}}</ref>\n\n==Victims==\nWortman killed at least 18 people, one of them RCMP Constable Heidi Stevenson, a 23-year veteran. He shot and wounded a second RCMP officer, who is in stable condition.<ref name=\"CBC3\"/><ref name=\"CBC\" /><ref name=\"global-news-rcmp-active-shooter-portapique-n-s\">{{Cite news|last=Quon|first=Alexander|url=https://globalnews.ca/news/6838880/rcmp-active-shooter-portapique-n-s/|title=17 dead, including one RCMP officer, after shooting spree in Portapique, N.S.|date=April 19, 2020|access-date=April 19, 2020|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200419202613/https://globalnews.ca/news/6838880/rcmp-active-shooter-portapique-n-s/|archive-date=April 19, 2020|publisher=[[Global News]]|last2=Stephenson|first2=Mercedes}}</ref> At least one other person was injured.<ref name=\"CBC3\" /> According to Commissioner [[Brenda Lucki]], some of his first victims were closely connected to him, but as he continued, his targets became more random.<ref name=\"nyt-nova-scotia-shooting-gabriel-wortman\" /> The dead are believed to have died from gunshot wounds, but other causes are also being investigated.<ref name=\"CBC3\" /><ref name=\"BBC\" /> The RCMP expects to find more bodies within the remnants of five structure fires.<ref name=\"CTV4\">{{cite web|url=https://www.ctvnews.ca/canada/nova-scotia-rampage-results-in-18-victims-16-crime-scenes-1.4903398|title=Nova Scotia rampage results in 18 victims, 16 crime scenes|date=April 20, 2020|work=[[CTV News]]|first=Meredith|last=MacLeod|accessdate=April 20, 2020}}</ref>\n\n==Perpetrator==\nThe RCMP identified the perpetrator as Gabriel Wortman, a [[denturist]] working in the Halifax area. He owned real estate in Portapique and [[Dartmouth, Nova Scotia|Dartmouth]].<ref name=\"CBC\"/><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.theguardian.com/world/2020/apr/20/nova-scotia-shooting-gunman-profile-quiet-gentle-denturist|title=Nova Scotia shooting: shock and surprise at killings by denturist|first=Leyland|last=Cecco|date=April 19, 2020|accessdate=April 19, 2020|website=The Guardian}}</ref> He attended [[Riverview High School (New Brunswick)|Riverview High School]] in New Brunswick and aspired to be a police officer.<ref name=\":1\">{{Cite web|url=https://atlantic.ctvnews.ca/just-unbelievable-neighbours-of-nova-scotia-shooting-suspect-shocked-by-news-1.4903021|title='Just unbelievable': Neighbours of Nova Scotia shooting suspect shocked by news|date=April 19, 2020|website=CTV News|language=en|access-date=April 20, 2020}}</ref> Acquaintances described him as a house-proud and polite man who often spent time at a seasonal home near [[Cobequid Bay]].<ref name=\"CTV5\">{{cite news|url=https://www.ctvnews.ca/canada/what-we-know-about-the-nova-scotia-rampage-suspect-1.4903920|title=What we know about the Nova Scotia rampage suspect|publisher=CTV News|last=Bogart|first=Nicole|date=April 20, 2020|accessdate=April 20, 2020}}</ref>\n\nWortman had a hobby of buying law enforcement memorabilia and refurbishing old police cruisers. One person called his home a \"shrine\" for the RCMP.<ref name=\":0\">{{cite news|url=https://www.theglobeandmail.com/canada/article-nova-scotia-mass-shooter-was-a-denturist-with-an-obsession-for/|title=Nova Scotia mass shooter was a denturist with an obsession for policing|publisher=The Globe and Mail|last1=Woo|first1=Andrew|last2=Mercer|first2=Greg|date=April 19, 2020|accessdate=April 20, 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200420055810/https://www.theglobeandmail.com/canada/article-nova-scotia-mass-shooter-was-a-denturist-with-an-obsession-for/|archive-date=April 20, 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> He stored the two old police cruisers that he bought behind his dental clinic.<ref name=\":1\" /><ref name=\"CTV5\" />\n\nNeighbours said Wortman struggled with [[alcohol use]] and his profitable business was impacted by the [[2020 coronavirus pandemic in Nova Scotia|coronavirus pandemic]], which forced all non-essential dental services to cease.<ref name=\":0\" />\n\n==Reactions==\n[[Nova Scotia Premier]] [[Stephen McNeil]] told reporters, \"This is one of the most senseless acts of violence in our province's history.\" He expressed his condolences to the residents affected and the families of the victims.<ref name=\"CTV2\">{{cite news|url=https://atlantic.ctvnews.ca/shooting-one-of-the-most-senseless-acts-of-violence-in-nova-scotia-s-history-premier-1.4902917|title=Shooting 'one of the most senseless acts of violence' in Nova Scotia's history: premier|last=Jerrett|first=Andrea|publisher=CTV News|accessdate=April 19, 2020|date=April 19, 2020}}</ref> Prime Minister [[Justin Trudeau]] also expressed his condolences.<ref name=\"CBC\" /> During his morning address from [[Rideau Cottage]] on April 20, he reaffirmed his commitment to strengthening gun control.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.ctvnews.ca/politics/trudeau-reiterates-gun-control-commitment-in-wake-of-mass-shooting-1.4903966|title=Trudeau reiterates gun control commitment in wake of mass shooting|publisher=CTV News|last=Gilmore|first=Rachel|date=April 20, 2020|accessdate=April 20, 2020}}</ref> Flags across Canada were lowered to [[half-mast]],<ref name=\"Guardian2\">{{cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/world/2020/apr/20/nova-scotia-shooting-friends-family-pay-tribute-victims|title=Nova Scotia shooting: friends and family pay tribute to 'beautiful souls' lost in rampage|publisher=The Guardian|last=Cecco|first=Leyland|date=April 20, 2020|accessdate=April 20, 2020}}</ref> and the [[House of Commons of Canada|House of Commons]] observed a moment of silence for the victims.<ref>{{cite web| url=https://www.cbc.ca/news/politics/trudeau-nova-scotia-shooting-1.5538301| title='We're going to get through this together': Trudeau calls for unity after mass killing| website=CBC News| date=April 20, 2020| accessdate=April 20, 2020| url-status=live| archive-url=http://archive.is/7qFSQ| archive-date=April 20, 2020}}</ref>\n\nThe [[White House]] released a statement that condemned the killings and expressed US President [[Donald Trump]] and US First Lady [[Melania Trump]]'s condolences.<ref name=\"CNN\">{{cite news|url=https://www.cnn.com/2020/04/20/americas/nova-scotia-shooting-monday/index.html|title=Gunman evaded police for nearly 12 hours and killed at least 18 in one of Canada's deadliest mass shootings|publisher=CNN|last1=McLaughlin|first1=Eliott C.|last2=Newton|first2=Paula|date=April 20, 2020|accessdate=April 20, 2020}}</ref>\n\n==See also==\n* [[Moncton shooting]]\n* [[List of massacres in Canada]]\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n[[Category:2020 crimes in Canada]]\n[[Category:2020 in Nova Scotia]]\n[[Category:2020 mass shootings]]\n[[Category:2020 mass shootings in North America]]\n[[Category:2020 murders in North America]]\n[[Category:2020s mass shootings in North America]]\n[[Category:21st-century mass murder in North America]]\n[[Category:April 2020 crimes]]\n[[Category:April 2020 events in Canada]]\n[[Category:Arson in Canada]]\n[[Category:Arson in the 2020s]]\n[[Category:Attacks in 2020]]\n[[Category:Crime in Nova Scotia]]\n[[Category:Death in Nova Scotia]]\n[[Category:Deaths by firearm in Canada]]\n[[Category:Mass shootings in Canada]]\n[[Category:Mass murder in Canada]]\n[[Category:Royal Canadian Mounted Police]]\n[[Category:Spree shootings in Canada]]\n", "name_user": "InedibleHulk", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eTimeline:Motorfolk.", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Nova_Scotia_killings"}
{"title_page": "Kannada cinema", "text_new": "{{short description|Films in Kannada language}}\n{{Use Indian English|date=September 2017}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=May 2017}}\n{{Infobox cinema market\n| name                 = Kannada cinema\n| image                = PVR cinema bangalore.jpg\n| image_size           = 180px\n| alt                  =\n| caption              = PVR cinemas In [[Bengaluru]]\n| screens              = 650 Single-screens in [[Karnataka]] \n| screens_per_capita   =\n| distributors         = \n* Vajreshwari Combines\n* Eshwari Productions\n*[[Chamundeshwari Studios]]\n*[[Jayanna Combines]]\n*[[Rockline Entertainments]]\n*[[Paramvah Studios]]\n*[[Pushkar Films]]\n*[[Lokesh Productions]]\n*[[Felis Creations]]\n*PRK Production\n*Thoogudeepa Productions\n*[[Hombale Films]]\n*Vrushbhadri Productions\n*[[Paramvah Studios]]\n| produced_year        = \n| produced_ref         = \n| produced_total       = \n| produced_fictional   =\n| produced_animated    =\n| produced_documentary =\n| admissions_year      =\n| admissions_ref       =\n| admissions_total     =\n| admissions_per_capita =\n| admissions_national  =\n| box_office_year      = 2018 till September\n| box_office_ref       = <ref name=\"auto\">{{cite web|title=The Digital March Media & Entertainment in South India|url=http://www2.deloitte.com/content/dam/Deloitte/in/Documents/technology-media-telecommunications/in-tmt-economic-contribution-of-motion-picture-and-television-industry-noexp.pdf|publisher=Deloitte|accessdate=July 2018}}</ref>\n| box_office_total     = \n| box_office_national  = \n}}\n{{Indian cinema}}\n'''Kannada cinema''', also known as '''Sandalwood''', is the segment of [[Indian cinema]]<ref name=\"deccanherald.com\">[http://www.dnaindia.com/entertainment/slideshow-sandalwood-rechristened-1518654#top] Link referring rechristening of sandalwod as chandanavana at world kannada summit</ref> dedicated to the production of motion pictures in the [[Kannada language]] widely spoken in the state of [[Karnataka]].<ref>{{cite book |author=Shampa Banerjee, Anil Srivastava|title= One Hundred Indian Feature Films: An Annotated Filmography|origyear=1988|year= 1988|publisher= Taylor & Francis|isbn= 0-8240-9483-2}}</ref><ref>[http://www.deccanherald.com/content/124106/when-rained-films.html When it rained films]. Deccanherald.com. Retrieved on 2017-07-29.</ref><ref>[http://www.filmfed.org/singlescreen.html \"Statewise number of single screens\"]. chitraloka.com (1913-05-03). Retrieved on 2013-07-29.</ref> The 1934 film ''[[Sati Sulochana]]'' directed by [[Yaragudipati Varada Rao|Y. V. Rao]] was the first talkie film in the Kannada language.<ref name=\"Rediff\">[http://www.rediff.com/movies/2006/apr/13ms.htm Dr.Raj's impact on Kannada cinema] [[Rediff.com]]</ref><ref>{{cite news |title=First film to talk in Kannada  |url=http://www.hindu.com/thehindu/fr/2004/12/31/stories/2004123102420300.htm |date=31 December 2004 |work=[[The Hindu]] |location=Chennai, India}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |title=A revolutionary filmmaker  |url= http://www.hindu.com/thehindu/fr/2003/08/22/stories/2003082201400400.htm|date= 22 August 2003|work=[[The Hindu]]|location=Chennai, India}}</ref> It was also the first film starring [[Subbaiah Naidu]], and was the first motion picture screened in the erstwhile [[Mysore Kingdom]].<ref name=\"ss\">{{cite news|url=http://www.hindu.com/fr/2004/12/31/stories/2004123102420300.htm|title=First film to talk in Kannada|work=Online Edition of the Hindu, dated 31 December 2004|accessdate=21 April 2007|location=Chennai, India|date=31 December 2004}}</ref> The film was produced by [[Chamanlal Doongaji]], who in 1932 founded ''South India Movietone'' in [[Bengaluru]].<ref name=thehindu>{{cite news |last1=Khajane |first1=Muralidhara |title=Philatelic show to mark 78th anniversary of \u2018Sati Sulochana' |url=https://www.thehindu.com/news/national/karnataka/philatelic-show-to-mark-78th-anniversary-of-sati-sulochana/article2929333.ece/amp/ |accessdate=3 September 2018 |work=The Hindu |date=25 February 2012 |language=en-IN}}</ref><ref name=dailyhunt>{{cite news |title=Wealth of material found on first Kannada talkie - Deccan Herald {{!}} DailyHunt |url=https://m.dailyhunt.in/news/bangladesh/english/deccan+herald-epaper-deccan/wealth+of+material+found+on+first+kannada+talkie-newsid-85780599 |accessdate=3 September 2018 |work=DailyHunt |language=en}}</ref>\n\nMajor literary works have been adapted to the Kannada screen such as [[B. V. Karanth]]'s ''[[Chomana Dudi]]'' (1975), [[Girish Karnad]]'s ''[[Kaadu (1973 Kannada film)|Kaadu]]'' (1973), [[Pattabhirama Reddy Tikkavarapu|Pattabhirama Reddy]]'s ''[[Samskara (film)|Samskara]]'' (1970) (based on a novel by [[U. R. Ananthamurthy]]), which won the Bronze Leopard at [[Locarno International Film Festival]],<ref>{{cite web|url=http://1nellore.com/1849/tikkavarapu-pattabhirama-reddy-poet-film-maker-of-international-fame/|title=Tikkavarapu Pattabhirama Reddy \u2013 Poet, Film maker of international fame from Nellore - 1Nellore.com|publisher=|access-date=26 January 2016|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20141006102018/http://1nellore.com/1849/tikkavarapu-pattabhirama-reddy-poet-film-maker-of-international-fame/|archive-date=6 October 2014|url-status=dead}}</ref> and [[T. S. Nagabharana]]'s [[Mysore Mallige (film)|Mysuru Mallige]] (based on the works of acclaimed poet [[K. S. Narasimhaswamy]]).<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.bharatmovies.com/director/ts-nagabharana-movies.htm|title=TS Nagabharana movies list|website=www.bharatmovies.com|access-date=2016-11-04}}</ref>\n\nKannada cinema is known for producing experimental works such as [[Girish Kasaravalli]]'s ''[[Ghatashraddha]]'' (1977), which won the Ducats Award at the Manneham Film Festival Germany,<ref>{{cite web |title= Asiatic Film Mediale |url= http://www.asiaticafilmmediale.it/2002/uk/intro.html |publisher= asiaticafilmmediale.it|url-status= dead |archiveurl= https://web.archive.org/web/20081116041627/http://www.asiaticafilmmediale.it/2002/uk/intro.html |archivedate= 16 November 2008 |df= dmy-all }}</ref> ''[[Dweepa]]'' (2002), which won Best Film at [[Moscow International Film Festival]],<ref>{{cite web |title= Girish Kasaravalli to be felicitated |url= http://www.thehindu.com/todays-paper/tp-national/tp-karnataka/girish-kasaravalli-to-be-felicitated/article1765035.ece |publisher=[[The Hindu]]|date= 25 April 2011 |accessdate= 25 March 2014}}</ref><ref name=\"awa\">{{cite web|url=http://www.hinduonnet.com/fline/fl1920/stories/20021011005912100.htm|title=A genius of theatre|work=The Frontline|date=12\u201325 October 2002|accessdate=2009-03-14}}</ref> [[Singeetam Srinivasa Rao]]'s silent film ''[[Pushpaka Vimana (1987 film)|Pushpaka Vimana]]'' (1987), screened at the [[Cannes Film Festival]], [[Ram Gopal Varma]]'s docudrama  ''[[Killing Veerappan]]'' (2016), and [[Prashanth Neel]]'s [[Historical drama]], ''[[K.G.F: Chapter 1]]'' (2018),<ref name=\"Oscar nominees among 240 films to be screened during Biffes\">{{cite web | url=http://www.thehindu.com/news/national/karnataka/Oscar-nominees-among-240-films-to-be-screened-during-Biffes/article17104930.ece | title=Oscar nominees among 240 films to be screened during Biffes | publisher=The Hindu | accessdate=27 January 2017}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.newindianexpress.com/entertainment/kannada/Killing-Veerappan-is-a-Slick-RGV-Thriller/2016/01/02/article3206836.ece|title=Killing Veerappan is a Slick RGV Thriller|work=The New Indian Express}}</ref> which became the first Kannada language film to have grossed \u20b9250 crores worldwide at the box office.<ref>{{cite|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190113152018/https://www.firstpost.com/entertainment/kgf-becomes-first-kannada-film-to-break-into-rs-200-cr-club-njan-prakashan-declared-blockbuster-5862501.html/amp|title=KGF becomes first Kannada film to break into Rs 200 cr club; Njan Prakashan declared blockbuster|date=2019-01-09|archivedate=2018-01-13|work=Firstpost}}</ref>\n\n==Early history==\n[[File:Honnappa Bhagavathar 1948.jpg|thumb|150px|upright|right|Kannada film doyen [[Honnappa Bhagavathar]]]]\n[[File:Rajkumar 2009 stamp of India.jpg|thumb|150px|upright|right|[[Rajkumar (actor)|Rajkumar]] on a 2009 stamp in India]]\nIn 1934, the first Kannada [[talkie]], ''[[Sati Sulochana]]'',<ref>[http://www.hinduonnet.com/thehindu/fr/2004/12/31/stories/2004123102420300.htm \"First film to talk in Kannada\"] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20070105012711/http://www.hinduonnet.com/thehindu/fr/2004/12/31/stories/2004123102420300.htm |date=5 January 2007 }} article in ''The Hindu''</ref> appeared in theatres, followed by ''[[Bhakta Dhruva]]'' (aka ''Dhruva Kumar''). ''Sati Sulochana'' was shot in [[Kolhapur]] at the Chatrapathi studio; most filming, sound recording, and post-production was done in [[Chennai]].<ref name=\"Routledge\">{{cite book|author1=K. Moti Gokulsing|author2=Wimal Dissanayake|title=Routledge Handbook of Indian Cinemas|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=djUFmlFbzFkC|date=17 April 2013|publisher=Routledge|isbn=978-1-136-77284-9}}</ref>\n\nIn 1949, [[Honnappa Bhagavathar]], who had earlier acted in Gubbi Veeranna's films, produced ''[[Bhakta Kumbara]]'' and starred in the lead role along with [[Pandaribai]]. In 1955, Bhagavathar again produced a Kannada film, ''[[Mahakavi Kalidasa]]'', in which he introduced actress [[B. Saroja Devi]].<ref name=\"Routledge\"/> [[B. S. Ranga]] was an Indian photographer, actor, writer, producer and director made many landmark movies in [[Kannada]], under Vikram Studios.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.thehindu.com/features/cinema/ratnapuri-ilavarasi-1960/article6229101.ece\n|title=Ratnapuri Ilavarasi (1960)|work=[[The Hindu]]|date=19 July 2014|accessdate=5 April 2018|last=Guy|first=Randor|authorlink=Randor Guy|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170731094156/http://www.thehindu.com/features/cinema/ratnapuri-ilavarasi-1960/article6229101.ece|url-status=live\n| archivedate=31 July 2017}}</ref>\n\n==Mainstream==\n[[Matinee idol]], [[Rajkumar (actor)|Rajkumar]] entered Kannada cinema after his long stint as a dramatist with [[Gubbi Veeranna]]'s ''Gubbi Drama Company'', which he joined at the age of eight, before he got his first break as a lead in the 1954 film ''[[Bedara Kannappa]]''.<ref name=\"Rajakumar, king of Kannada cinema\">{{cite web|title=Rajakumar, king of Kannada cinema|url=http://www.rediff.com/movies/report/rajobit/20060412.htm|publisher=Rediff.com|accessdate=24 April 2017|date=12 April 2006}}</ref>\n\nHe went on to essay a variety of roles and excelling in portraying mythological and historical characters in films such as ''[[Bhakta Kanakadasa]]'' (1960), ''[[Ranadheera Kanteerava]]'' (1960), ''[[Satya Harishchandra (1965 Kannada film)|Satya Harishchandra]]'' (1965), ''[[Immadi Pulikeshi (film)|Immadi Pulikeshi]]'' (1967), ''[[Sri Krishnadevaraya (film)|Sri Krishnadevaraya]]'' (1970), ''[[Bhakta Kumbara]]'' (1974), ''[[Mayura (film)|Mayura]]'' (1975), ''[[Babruvahana (film)|Babruvahana]]'' (1977) and ''[[Bhakta Prahlada (1983 film)|Bhakta Prahlada]]'' (1983). His wife [[Parvathamma Rajkumar]] founded Film production and distribution company, Vajreshwari Combines.<ref name=\"Rajakumar, king of Kannada cinema\"/>\n\nMethod actor [[Shankar Nag]] received the inaugural [[IFFI Best Actor Award (Male)]]: Silver Peacock Award\" at the [[7th International Film Festival of India]] for his work in the film ''[[Ondanondu Kaladalli]]''.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=EKo-DwAAQBAJ&pg=PT157&lpg=PT157&dq=iffi+girish+karnad+1979&source=bl&ots=i-oQyInjhS&sig=ouE2Erj4qaPNVQsqJMuI8UEP7Mc&hl=en&sa=X&ved=0ahUKEwjwpca06c_YAhUjSo8KHRMmBgIQ6AEIUTAJ#v=onepage&q=iffi+girish+karnad+1979&f=false|title=Conscience of The Race|first=BIBEKANANDA|last=RAY|date=5 April 2017|publisher=Publications Division Ministry of Information & Broadcasting|via=Google Books}}</ref> He is the younger brother of actor [[Anant Nag]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://articles.timesofindia.indiatimes.com/2013-03-14/news-interviews/37712791_1_shankar-nag-documentary-auto-raja|title=This one's for Shankar Nag - Times of India|publisher=}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=YbG4HPNDlsk|title=Shankar Nag Last Interview - Part 2|first=|last=Anand Chandrashekar|date=7 November 2009|publisher=|via=YouTube}}</ref> [[M. V. Vasudeva Rao]] was starred in over 200 films in his career; however, post ''[[Chomana Dudi]]'', he only played minor roles.<ref>{{cite web|last1=Rao|first1=M. K. Bhaskar|title=A natural|url=http://www.deccanherald.com/deccanherald/apr13/at3.htm|website=Deccan Herald|accessdate=2 May 2017|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20020425090527/http://www.deccanherald.com/deccanherald/apr13/at3.htm|archivedate=25 April 2002|date=14 April 2002}}</ref>\n\n[[Vishnuvardhan (actor)|Vishnuvardhan]] entered Kannada cinema with the National Award-winning movie ''[[Vamshavruksha]]'' (1972) directed by [[Girish Karnad]] based on the novel written by [[S. L. Bhyrappa]]. His first lead role was in ''[[Naagarahaavu]]'', directed by [[Puttanna Kanagal]] and based on a novel by [[T. R. Subba Rao]]. It was the first in Kannada film history to complete 100 days in three main theatres of Bangalore. In his 37-year career, he has played a variety of roles in more than 200 films.<ref>{{cite news| url=http://www.thehindu.com/features/cinema/vishnuvardhan-helped-me-to-get-stardom-rajinikanth/article76796.ece | location=Chennai, India | work=The Hindu | title=Vishnuvardhan helped me to get stardom: Rajinikanth | date=7 January 2010}}</ref>\n\nWith his debut in [[Puttanna Kanagal]]'s National Award-winning Kannada film ''[[Naagarahaavu]]'' (1972), [[Ambareesh]]'s acting career commenced with a brief phase of portraying antagonistic and supporting characters. After establishing himself as a lead actor portraying rebellious characters on screen in a number of commercially successful films, he earned the moniker \"rebel star\".<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.deccanherald.com/content/174720/when-rebel-star-rewinds-past.html|title=When 'Rebel Star' rewinds past days in Mysore|newspaper=Deccan Herald|date=20 September 2014}}</ref> He also earned the nickname ''Mandyada Gandu'' (English: Man of [[Mandya]])<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.thehindu.com/todays-paper/tp-national/tp-karnataka/mandyada-gandu-gets-rousing-welcome/article5907186.ece|title=\u2018Mandyada Gandu\u2019 gets rousing welcome|newspaper=The Hindu|date=13 April 2013}}</ref>\n\n[[B. Saroja Devi]] is One of the most successful female leads in the history of Indian cinema, she acted in around 200 films in over six decades.<ref>[http://www.chitramala.com/articles/saroja-devi-4189.html Documentary on legendary Saroja Devi - Chitramala.com] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110711020420/http://www.chitramala.com/articles/saroja-devi-4189.html |date=11 July 2011 }}</ref><ref name=\"ToI_greatest_2013\">{{cite news |url=http://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/entertainment/kannada/movies/news/B-Saroja-Devi-in-the-list-of-greatest-Indianactresses-ever/articleshow/19895895.cms |title=B Saroja Devi in the list of greatest Indian actresses ever |author=Taniya Talukdar |date=5 May 2013 |newspaper=The Times of India }}</ref> She is known by the epithets \"''Abinaya Saraswathi''\" ([[Saraswati|Saraswathi]] of acting) in Kannada and \"''Kannadathu Paingili''\" (Kannada's Parrot) in Tamil.<ref name=\"ToI_greatest_2013\"/>\n\n==Neo-realistic Cinema==\n{{main|Parallel cinema}}\nKannada Cinema majorly contributed to the [[Parallel cinema]] movement of India.<ref name=\"Kasaravalli\">{{cite|url=https://www.thenewsminute.com/article/parallel-cinema-girish-kasaravalli-look-kannada-industrys-stalwart-filmmaker-72172|title=The parallel cinema of Girish Kasaravalli: A look at Kannada industry's stalwart filmmaker|date=2017-11-07|work=The News Minute}}</ref> Directors like [[Girish Kasaravalli]],<ref name=\"Kasaravalli\"/> [[Girish Karnad]],<ref name=\"Karnad\">{{cite|url=https://www.thehindu.com/entertainment/kannadas-parallel-cinema-loses-its-star/article26662943.ece|title=Kannada's parallel cinema loses its star|date=2019-03-28|work=The Hindu}}</ref> [[G. V. Iyer]]<ref name=\"Karnad\"/> were the early names to join the movement. [[T. S. Nagabharana]]<ref>{{cite book |date=2003 |title=Cinema in India, Volume 3 |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=WQtlAAAAMAAJ&q=Puttanna+Kanagal&dq=Puttanna+Kanagal&hl=en&sa=X&ei=uqSgVfWxG5PSoATz-p6QBg&ved=0CDoQ6AEwBzge |publisher=Mangala Chandran |access-date=July 11, 2015}}</ref> and [[BV Karanth]] were also popular names in the movement. [[Puttanna Kanagal]]'s films were however considered as a bridge between the Mainstream and the Parallel Cinema.\n\n==Modern Era==\n[[Prakash Raj]] began his acting career with [[Doordarshan]] serials such as ''Bisilu Kudure'' (Kannada) and ''[[Guddada Bhootha]]'' ([[Tulu language|Tulu]] and Kannada).<ref>{{cite web|url=http://indianexpress.com/article/india/if-artistes-become-cowards-they-make-society-a-coward-prakash-raj-4975924/lite|title=If artistes become cowards, they make society a coward: Prakash Raj}}</ref> He later took up supporting roles in [[Kannada language|Kannada]] films such as ''Ramachari'', ''[[Ranadheera]]'', ''[[Nishkarsha]]'' and ''[[Lockup Death]]''. He was noticed for his dialogue delivery and histrionics. His breakthrough role came in ''[[Harakeya Kuri]]'', directed by [[K. S. L. Swamy]] starring Vishnuvardhan, with whom he had acted in other films such as ''[[Mithileya Seetheyaru]]'', ''[[Muthina Haara]]'' and ''[[Nishkarsha]]''. Prakash re-entered Kannada films through ''[[Nagamandala]]'' in 1997, directed by [[T. S. Nagabharana]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.firstpost.com/india/prakash-raj-exclusive-everyone-has-the-right-to-differ-but-this-is-orchestrated-trolling-and-you-cannot-threaten-me-with-continuous-abuse-4174937.html/amp|title=Prakash Raj exclusive: Everyone has the right to differ, but this is orchestrated trolling. And you cannot threaten me with continuous abuse}}</ref> Veteran Kannada actor [[Shakti Prasad]]'s son [[Arjun Sarja]] is known for his works in South Indian cinema.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.supergoodmovies.com/41510/sandalwood/four-films-announced-for-23rd-march-news-details |title=Archived copy |accessdate=2012-03-21 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120320165539/http://www.supergoodmovies.com/41510/sandalwood/four-films-announced-for-23rd-march-news-details |archivedate=20 March 2012 |df=dmy-all }}</ref> He was starred in works such as [[Prasad (2012 film)|Prasad]], the film was screened at the [[Berlin Film Festival]], and Arjun received the Karnataka State Award for his performance.<ref>[http://articles.timesofindia.indiatimes.com/2012-02-23/news-interviews/31090458_1_martin-gropius-bau-festival-director-indian-film]</ref>\n\n[[Sanchari Vijay]]'s portrayal of a transgender won him the [[National Film Award for Best Actor|National Best Actor Award]].<ref>{{cite web|title=Vijay bags National Award for Best Actor|url=http://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/entertainment/kannada/movies/news/Vijay-bags-National-Award-for-Best-Actor/articleshow/46676471.cms|publisher=timesofindia|date=24 March 2015|accessdate=2015-03-24}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=Sanchari Vijay Actor\u2013Profile and biography|url=http://cinetrooth.in/2015/06/21/sanchari-vijay-actor-profile-and-biography/|publisher=cinetrooth|date=21 June 2015|accessdate=22 August 2015}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=Vijay elated on winning best actor award|url=http://www.deccanherald.com/content/467499/vijay-elated-winning-actor-award.html|publisher=deccanherald|date=25 March 2015|accessdate=2015-03-26}}</ref> With the award win, Vijay became the third actor after [[M. V. Vasudeva Rao]], and [[Charuhasan]] to win the National Award for Best Actor for performing in a [[Kannada film]].<ref>http://www.rediff.com/movies/report/meet-the-first-kannada-actor-to-win-a-national-award-south/20150325.htm</ref>\n\n[[Shiva Rajkumar]] is known for his work in ''[[Janumada Jodi]]'', ''[[Anand (1986 film)|Anand]]'', ''[[Ratha Sapthami]]'', ''[[Nammoora Mandara Hoove]]'', ''[[Om]]'' ''[[Simhada Mari]]'', and ''[[Chigurida Kanasu]]''. He acted in ''[[Sugreeva (film)|Sugreeva]]'', which was shot in 18 hours. His ''[[Om (Kannada film)|Om]]'', directed by [[Upendra (actor)|Upendra]], set a trend of gangster movies in [[Kannada]] and other film industries in India. It continues to be shown even to this day.<ref>[http://kannada.oneindia.in/movies/news/2010/09/01-upendra-om-re-release-on-sept-3.html \u0caa\u0ccd\u0cb0\u0cc7\u0c95\u0ccd\u0cb7\u0c95\u0cb0 \u0c92\u0ca4\u0ccd\u0ca4\u0cbe\u0caf\u0ca6 \u0cae\u0cc7\u0cb0\u0cc6\u0c97\u0cc6 \u0cae\u0ca4\u0ccd\u0ca4\u0cc6 \u0cac\u0c82\u0ca6\u0cbf\u0ca6\u0cc6 \u0c93\u0c82!], One India, 1 September 2010</ref>\n\n[[Rockline Venkatesh]] founded [[Rockline Entertainments]] which has produced over twenty five films as of 2012.<ref name=\"63rdaward\">{{cite press_release|title=63rd National Film Awards|url=http://dff.nic.in/writereaddata/Winners_of_63rd_NFA_2015.pdf|format=PDF|publisher=[[Directorate of Film Festivals]]|date=28 March 2016|accessdate=28 March 2016}}</ref> New age actors [[Puneeth Rajkumar]], [[Rakshith Shetty]], and [[Yash (actor)|Yash]] are one of the highest-paid actors in Sandalwood.<ref>[http://www.ibtimes.co.in/box-office-collection-pk-mr-mrs-ramachari-dominate-bengaluru-collection-centres-619818 Box Office Collection: 'PK', 'Mr & Mrs Ramachari' Dominate Bengaluru Collection Centres]. Ibtimes.co.in (9 January 2015). Retrieved on 11 November 2016.</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.sify.com/movies/birthday-gift-to-yash-ramachari-to-enter-20-cr-club-soon-news-kannada-pbikMujcjecag.html|title=Birthday gift to Yash: Ramachari to enter cr club soon!|agency=www.sify.com|access-date=22 August 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190822145507/https://www.sify.com/movies/birthday-gift-to-yash-ramachari-to-enter-20-cr-club-soon-news-kannada-pbikMujcjecag.html|archive-date=22 August 2019|url-status=dead}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |title= 'Mr and Mrs Ramachari' Review: Audience Live Response |url= http://www.ibtimes.co.in/mr-mrs-ramachari-review-audience-live-response-618291 |publisher= ibtimes.co.in |date= 25 December 2014 |accessdate= 2 January 2015}}</ref> The [[Rakshith Shetty]] starrer ''[[Kirik Party]]'' opened to {{cn span|widespread acclaim from critics and audiences alike|date=January 2020}} and went on to become the [[List of highest-grossing Indian films|highest-grossing film]] of the year by collecting \u20b950 [[crore]]<ref name=\"ittt\">{{cite web|url=http://www.ibtimes.co.in/rakshit-shettys-kirik-party-telugu-remake-rights-sold-talks-other-language-rights-721075|title=Rakshit Shetty's Kirik Party dubbed by malayalam movie premam and Telugu remake rights sold; talks on for other language rights|publisher=International Business Times|date=28 March 2017|accessdate=28 March 2017}}</ref> against production budget \u20b94 crore,<ref name=\"th\">{{cite web|title=The budget of \u2018Kirik Party\u2019 would be around \u20b94crore|url=http://www.thehindu.com/news/national/karnataka/rakshith-shettys-kirik-party-to-go-on-the-floors-in-march/article8191273.ece\n|work=The Hindu}}</ref> and completed 150-days in main centers of [[Karnataka]],<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.indiatoday.in/amp/movies/regional-cinema/story/krik-party-rakshit-shetty-rashmika-mandanna-celebrate-150-days-981176-2017-06-06|title=Kirik Party completes 150 days: Rakshit Shetty, Rashmika Mandanna celebrate with fans|website=India Today}}</ref>\n\nIn 2018, [[K.G.F: Chapter 1]] became the first [[Kannada]] film to gross \u20b9100 crores, \u20b9200 crores and \u20b9250 crores at the box office. A sequel is slated to release on 23 October 2020.<ref>https://www.indiatoday.in/amp/movies/regional-cinema/story/yash-reveals-he-has-approached-sanjay-dutt-for-kgf-chapter-2-1452187-2019-02-09</ref>\n\n==Film Score==\nComposer [[Hamsalekha]] is usually referred to by the title ''Naadha Brahma'' (English: The [[Brahma]] of Music) who is considered to be the major cause for the change in the music composing and lyric writing style which would appeal much to the younger generation. He integrated folk and introduced western musical sensibilities into the Kannada cinema.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.chitraloka.com/news/1472-hamsalekha-60.html|title=Hamsalekha 60|publisher=Chitraloka|date=23 June 2011}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.indiaglitz.com/dr-hamsalekha-now-kannada-news-107448|title=Dr. Hamsalekha now|publisher=Indiaglitz|date=14 May 2014}}</ref>\n\n[[Mano Murthy]] scored the blockbuster film [[Mungaru Male]] starring [[Ganesh (actor)|Ganesh]] and [[Pooja Gandhi]]. Upon the album's release, it topped the charts with the song \"[[Anisuthide]]\" receiving significant radio and TV air time.<ref name = hindu>{{cite news |title='Mungaru Male' still tops the charts |url=http://www.thehindu.com/todays-paper/tp-national/tp-karnataka/mungaru-male-still-tops-the-charts/article1843484.ece |newspaper=The Hindu |date=17 May 2014 |accessdate=6 November 2014}}</ref> The album emerged as a massive success topping every Kannada music chart. It was reported that by mid-May 2007, over 200,000 copies were sold in [[compact disc]]s.<ref>{{cite news |title='Mungaru Male' album a mega hit |url=http://www.highbeam.com/doc/1P3-1273374021.html |accessdate=10 October 2015 |work=Hindustan Times |date=18 May 2007 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20151010052639/http://www.highbeam.com/doc/1P3-1273374021.html |archivedate=10 October 2015}}</ref>\n\n==Film Schools==\nThe first government institute in India to start technical courses related to films was established in 1941 named as occupational institute then called the Sri Jayachamarajendra (S J) Polytechnic in [[Bangalore|Bengaluru]]. In September 1996, two specialized courses, Cinematography and Sound & Television were separated and the [[Government Film and Television Institute]] was started at [[Hesaraghatta]], under the World Bank Assisted Project for Technician Development in India. There is an Online Film school named 'Sushupti Dreams' on Youtube where you can learn filmmaking for free. <ref>{{cite web|title=GFTI|url=http://www.filminstitutebangalore.com/index.htm|website=www.filminstitutebangalore.com|accessdate=22 August 2014|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://archive.today/20140821235404/http://www.filminstitutebangalore.com/index.htm|archivedate=21 August 2014|df=dmy-all}}</ref>\n\n==State Awards==\n[[File:Karnataka Chalanachitra Kalavidara Sangha-img.jpg|thumb|150px|right|Karnataka Chalanachitra Kalavidara Sangha in [[Chamrajpet|Chamrajapet]]]]\n* [[Karnataka State Film Awards]]\n* [[Udaya Film Awards]]\n* [[Suvarna Film Awards]]\n\n==State Festivals==\n* [[Bangalore International Film Festival]]<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.biffes.in/|title=Bengaluru International Film Festival - BIFFES|work=Bengaluru International Film Festival}}</ref>\n\n==Other Awards==\n* [[Filmfare Awards South]]\n* [[SIIMA Awards]]\n* [[IIFA Utsavam]]\n* [[Mirchi Music Awards South]]\n* [[South Scope|South Scope Awards]]\n{{clear}}\n\n==See also==\n* [[List of Kannada-language films]]\n* [[Media in Karnataka]]\n* [[Cinema of India]]\n* [[Media of India]]\n* [[List of Kannada film actresses]]\n\n==Highest-grossing Kannada films by year==\n{| style=\"margin:auto; margin:auto;\" class=\"wikitable sortable\"\n|-\n! Rank\n! Film\n! Year\n! Director(s)\n! Studio(s)\n! Worldwide gross\n! {{Tooltip|Ref.|Reference(s)}}\n|- \n| 1 \n| ''[[K.G.F: Chapter 1]]'' \n| 2018\n| [[Prashanth Neel]]\n| Hombale Films\n| {{INRConvert|243|c}}\u2013{{INRConvert|250|c}}\n|<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.timesnownews.com/amp/entertainment/box-office/article/yash-starrer-kgf-collects-rs-243-10-crore-at-the-worldwide-box-office-in-50-days-will-it-make-rs-250-crore/363115|title=Kannada Cinema's Pride! Yash starrer KGF collects Rs 243.10 crore