{"title_page": "Steph Ryan", "text_new": "{{Use dmy dates|date=June 2015}}\n{{Use Australian English|date=June 2015}}\n{{Infobox AM\n|honorific-prefix = \n|name        = Steph Ryan\n|honorific-suffix = [[Victorian Legislative Assembly|MP]]\n|image       = \n|alt         = \n|caption     = \n|constituency_AM = [[Electoral district of Euroa|Euroa]]\n|assembly    = Victorian Legislative\n|majority    = \n|term_start  = 29 November 2014\n|term_end    = \n|predecessor = ''New seat''\n|successor   = \n|birth_date         = {{Birth date and age|df=y|1986|6|20}}\n|birth_place        = [[Murchison, Victoria]], Australia\n|death_date         = \n|death_place        = \n|restingplace       = \n|restingplacecoordinates = \n|birthname          = \n|nationality        = Australian\n|party              = [[National Party of Australia \u2013 Victoria|National Party]]\n|spouse             = \n|relations          = \n|children           = \n|alma_mater         = [[RMIT University]]\n|committees         = \n|portfolio          = \n|religion           = \n|occupation = Journalist, media advisor\n|website = http://www.stephryan.com.au/\n}}\n'''Stephanie Maureen Ryan''' (born 20 June 1986) is an Australian politician. She has been a [[National Party of Australia \u2013 Victoria|National Party]] member of the [[Victorian Legislative Assembly]] since November 2014, representing the Legislative Assembly seat of [[Electoral district of Euroa|Euroa]].<ref>{{Cite web|url = http://www.abc.net.au/news/vic-election-2014/guide/lowa/|title = Lowan Results|date = |accessdate = 6 December 2014|website = ABC News|publisher = |last = |first = }}</ref>\n\nShe had served as a country journalist and senior adviser to various state MPs including Liberal Premier [[Ted Baillieu]]<ref>{{Cite web|url = https://www.abc.net.au/news/2014-08-08/coalition-puts-up-united-front-despite-euroa-rift/5658350|title = Victorian Coalition puts up united front despite rift over Euroa contest|date = |accessdate = 1 March 2020|website = ABC News|publisher = |last = |first = }}</ref> and members of the Victorian Nationals' leadership team prior to her own election.  On 3 December 2014, Ryan was elected as deputy leader of the Nationals in the [[Victorian Parliament]].<ref>{{Cite web|url = http://www.sbs.com.au/news/article/2014/12/03/walsh-ryan-new-vic-nats-leadership-duo|title = Walsh, Ryan new Vic Nats leadership duo|date = |accessdate = 6 December 2014|website = SBS News|publisher = |last = |first = }}</ref> On 17 December, she was made Shadow Minister for Training, Skills and Apprenticeships and Shadow Minister for Young Victorians.<ref>{{Cite web|url = http://www.abc.net.au/news/2014-12-17/victorian-coalition-announces-their-shadow-cabinet/5973004|title = Victorian Coalition announces shadow cabinet of 24, with 10 new faces, led by Matthew Guy|date = |accessdate = 18 December 2014|website = ABC News|publisher = |last = |first = }}</ref> Following the 2018 election Ryan was given the portfolios of Water, Public Transport (Regional), Gaming and Liquor Regulation.<ref>{{Cite web|url = https://vic.liberal.org.au/news/2018-12-17/liberal-nationals-shadow-cabinet|title = LIBERAL NATIONALS SHADOW CABINET|date = |accessdate = 1 March 2020|website = The Age|publisher = |last = |first = }}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*{{Official website|http://www.stephryan.com.au/}}\n* [http://vicvote.review/assembly/members/Steph%20Ryan.html Parliamentary voting record of Steph Ryan at Victorian Parliament Tracker]\n\n{{s-start}}\n{{s-par|au-vic-la}}\n|-\n{{s-non|reason=New seat}}\n{{s-ttl|title=Member for [[Electoral district of Euroa|Euroa]]|years=2014\u2013present}}\n{{s-inc}}\n{{s-ppo}}\n{{s-bef|before=[[Peter Walsh (Victorian politician)|Peter Walsh]]}}\n{{s-ttl|title=Deputy Leader of the [[National Party of Australia \u2013 Victoria|National Party]] in Victoria|years=2014\u2013present}}\n{{s-inc}}\n{{s-end}}\n{{VicCurrentMLAs}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Ryan, Steph}}\n[[Category:1986 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:National Party of Australia members of the Parliament of Victoria]]\n[[Category:Members of the Victorian Legislative Assembly]]\n[[Category:RMIT University alumni]]\n[[Category:21st-century Australian politicians]]\n[[Category:Women members of the Victorian Legislative Assembly]]\n", "text_old": "{{Use dmy dates|date=June 2015}}\n{{Use Australian English|date=June 2015}}\n{{Infobox AM\n|honorific-prefix = \n|name        = Steph Ryan\n|honorific-suffix = [[Victorian Legislative Assembly|MP]]\n|image       = \n|alt         = \n|caption     = \n|constituency_AM = [[Electoral district of Euroa|Euroa]]\n|assembly    = Victorian Legislative\n|majority    = \n|term_start  = 29 November 2014\n|term_end    = \n|predecessor = ''New seat''\n|successor   = \n|birth_date         = {{Birth date and age|df=y|1986|6|20}}\n|birth_place        = [[Murchison, Victoria]], Australia\n|death_date         = \n|death_place        = \n|restingplace       = \n|restingplacecoordinates = \n|birthname          = \n|nationality        = Australian\n|party              = [[National Party of Australia \u2013 Victoria|National Party]]\n|spouse             = \n|relations          = \n|children           = \n|alma_mater         = [[RMIT University]]\n|committees         = \n|portfolio          = \n|religion           = \n|occupation = Journalist, media advisor\n|website = http://www.stephryan.com.au/\n}}\n'''Stephanie Maureen Ryan''' (born 20 June 1986) is an Australian politician. She has been a [[National Party of Australia \u2013 Victoria|National Party]] member of the [[Victorian Legislative Assembly]] since November 2014, representing the Legislative Assembly seat of [[Electoral district of Euroa|Euroa]].<ref>{{Cite web|url = http://www.abc.net.au/news/vic-election-2014/guide/lowa/|title = Lowan Results|date = |accessdate = 6 December 2014|website = ABC News|publisher = |last = |first = }}</ref>\n\nShe had served as a country journalist and senior adviser to various state MPs including Liberal Premier [[Ted Baillieu]]<ref>{{Cite web|url = https://www.abc.net.au/news/2014-08-08/coalition-puts-up-united-front-despite-euroa-rift/5658350|title = Victorian Coalition puts up united front despite rift over Euroa contest|date = |accessdate = 1 March 2020|website = ABC News|publisher = |last = |first = }}</ref> and members of the Victorian Nationals' leadership team prior to her own election.  On 3 December 2014, Ryan was elected as deputy leader of the Nationals in the [[Victorian Parliament]].<ref>{{Cite web|url = http://www.sbs.com.au/news/article/2014/12/03/walsh-ryan-new-vic-nats-leadership-duo|title = Walsh, Ryan new Vic Nats leadership duo|date = |accessdate = 6 December 2014|website = SBS News|publisher = |last = |first = }}</ref> On 17 December, she was made Shadow Minister for Training, Skills and Apprenticeships and Shadow Minister for Young Victorians.<ref>{{Cite web|url = http://www.abc.net.au/news/2014-12-17/victorian-coalition-announces-their-shadow-cabinet/5973004|title = Victorian Coalition announces shadow cabinet of 24, with 10 new faces, led by Matthew Guy|date = |accessdate = 18 December 2014|website = ABC News|publisher = |last = |first = }}</ref> Following the 2018 election Ryan was given the portfolios of Water, Public Transport (Regional), Gaming and Liquor Regulation.<ref>{{Cite web|url = https://vic.liberal.org.au/news/2018-12-17/liberal-nationals-shadow-cabinet|title = LIBERAL NATIONALS SHADOW CABINET|date = |accessdate = 1 March 2020|website = The Age|publisher = |last = |first = }}</ref>\n\nIn 2016 Ryan married her long-term lover, former [[Australian Labor Party]] City of Yarra Councillor Simon Huggins.<ref>{{Cite web|url = https://www.pressreader.com/australia/mcivor-times/20141217/281479274758734|title = Ryan puts Heathcote high on her 'must' list|date = |accessdate = 1 March 2020|website = The McIvor Times|publisher = |last = |first = }}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url = https://issuu.com/mcphersonmediagroup/docs/bella_magazine__issue_2__2016_april|title = If you can't stand the heat, stay out of the kitchen|date = |accessdate = 1 March 2020|website = Bella|publisher = The Riverine Times|last = |first = }}</ref> According to Ryan, it took her more than three years of asking before Huggins agreed to go out with her.<ref>{{Cite web|url = https://issuu.com/mcphersonmediagroup/docs/bella_magazine__issue_2__2016_april|title = If you can't stand the heat, stay out of the kitchen|date = |accessdate = 1 March 2020|website = Bella|publisher = The Riverine Times|last = |first = }}</ref> The relationship attracted much interest in the media given Ryan's status as deputy leader of Victoria's oldest anti-Labor political party and Huggins being a member of the Labor Left and strident advocate for LGBTI issues.<ref>{{Cite web|url = https://www.heraldsun.com.au/leader/inner-east/rainbow-crossing-tipped-for-smith-st-collingwood-under-council-plan/news-story/4ccd1a9dc1a69b19a1ac10f303b0ad21|title = Rainbow crossing tipped for Smith St, Collingwood under council plan|date = |accessdate = 1 March 2020|website = Daily Telegraph|publisher = |last =Price |first =Nic }}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url = https://www.theage.com.au/national/victoria/new-nationals-mp-stephanie-ryan-breaks-the-country-partys-mould-20141203-11z7qj.html|title = New Nationals MP Stephanie Ryan breaks the country party's mould|date = |accessdate = 1 March 2020|website = The Age|publisher = |last =Gray |first =Darren }}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*{{Official website|http://www.stephryan.com.au/}}\n* [http://vicvote.review/assembly/members/Steph%20Ryan.html Parliamentary voting record of Steph Ryan at Victorian Parliament Tracker]\n\n{{s-start}}\n{{s-par|au-vic-la}}\n|-\n{{s-non|reason=New seat}}\n{{s-ttl|title=Member for [[Electoral district of Euroa|Euroa]]|years=2014\u2013present}}\n{{s-inc}}\n{{s-ppo}}\n{{s-bef|before=[[Peter Walsh (Victorian politician)|Peter Walsh]]}}\n{{s-ttl|title=Deputy Leader of the [[National Party of Australia \u2013 Victoria|National Party]] in Victoria|years=2014\u2013present}}\n{{s-inc}}\n{{s-end}}\n{{VicCurrentMLAs}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Ryan, Steph}}\n[[Category:1986 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:National Party of Australia members of the Parliament of Victoria]]\n[[Category:Members of the Victorian Legislative Assembly]]\n[[Category:RMIT University alumni]]\n[[Category:21st-century Australian politicians]]\n[[Category:Women members of the Victorian Legislative Assembly]]\n", "name_user": "POPPYP223", "label": "unsafe", "comment": "(del paragraph 3: unnecessary and incorrect personal information)", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Steph_Ryan"}
{"title_page": "Earth (1957 film)", "text_new": "{{short description|1957 film}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=April 2020}}\n{{Infobox film\n| name           = Earth\n| film_name      = \u0417\u0435\u043c\u044f\n| image          = \n| caption        = \n| director       = [[Zahari Zhandov]]\n| producer       = [[Doncho Todorov]]\n| writer         = {{ubl|[[Veselin Hanchev]]|[[Elin Pelin]]}}\n| starring       = [[Bogomil Simeonov]]\n| music          = \n| cinematography = Boncho Karastoyanov\n| editing        = Elena Popova\n| distributor    = \n| released       = {{film date|1957|3|4|df=yes}}\n| runtime        = 102 minutes\n| country        = Bulgaria\n| language       = Bulgarian\n| budget         = \n}}\n\n'''''Earth''''' ({{lang-bg|'''\u0417\u0435\u043c\u044f'''|translit=Zemya}}) is a 1957 Bulgarian [[drama film]] directed by [[Zahari Zhandov]]. It was entered into the [[1957 Cannes Film Festival]].<ref name=\"festival-cannes.com\">{{cite web |url=http://www.festival-cannes.com/en/archives/ficheFilm/id/3524/year/1957.html |title=Festival de Cannes: Earth |accessdate=8 February 2009|work=festival-cannes.com}}</ref>\n\n==Cast==\n* [[Bogomil Simeonov]] - Enyo\n* [[Slavka Slavova]] - Stanka\n* [[Ginka Stancheva]] - Tzveta\n* [[Elena Hranova]] - Tzveta's Mother\n* [[Stefan Petrov]] - Ivan\n* [[Kunka Baeva]] - Ana\n* [[Borislav Ivanov (actor)|Borislav Ivanov]] - Bazuneka\n* [[Nikolay Doychev]] - Ilcho\n* [[Lyubomir Bobchevski]]\n* [[Naicho Petrov]]\n* [[Hristo Dinev]]\n* [[Stefan Kuyumdzhiev]]\n* [[Dimitar Peshev]]\n* [[Mara Andonova]]\n* [[Nikola Dadov]]\n* [[Teofan Chranov]]\n* [[Trifon Dzhonev]]\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*{{imdb title|id=0279526|title=Earth}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Earth}}\n[[Category:1957 films]]\n[[Category:Bulgarian films]]\n[[Category:Bulgarian-language films]]\n[[Category:1957 drama films]]\n[[Category:Bulgarian black-and-white films]]\n[[Category:Films directed by Zahari Zhandov]]\n[[Category:Bulgarian drama films]]\n{{Bulgaria-film-stub}}\n", "text_old": "{{short description|1957 film}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=December 2019}}\n{{Infobox film\n| name           = Earth\n| film_name      = \u0417\u0435\u043c\u044f\n| image          = \n| caption        = \n| director       = [[Zahari Zhandov]]\n| producer       = [[Doncho Todorov]]\n| writer         = {{ubl|[[Veselin Hanchev]]|[[Elin Pelin]]}}\n| starring       = [[Bogomil Simeonov]]\n| music          = \n| cinematography = Boncho Karastoyanov\n| editing        = Elena Popova\n| distributor    = \n| released       = {{film date|1957|3|4|df=yes}}\n| runtime        = 102 minutes\n| country        = Bulgaria\n| language       = Bulgarian\n| budget         = \n}}\n\n'''''Earth''''' ({{lang-bg|'''\u0417\u0435\u043c\u044f'''|translit=Zemya}}) is a 1957 Bulgarian [[drama film]] directed by [[Zahari Zhandov]]. It was entered into the [[1957 Cannes Film Festival]].<ref name=\"festival-cannes.com\">{{cite web |url=http://www.festival-cannes.com/en/archives/ficheFilm/id/3524/year/1957.html |title=Festival de Cannes: Earth |accessdate=8 February 2009|work=festival-cannes.com}}</ref>\n\n==Cast==\n* [[Bogomil Simeonov]] - Enyo\n* [[Slavka Slavova]] - Stanka\n* [[Ginka Stancheva]] - Tzveta\n* [[Elena Hranova]] - Tzveta's Mother\n* [[Stefan Petrov]] - Ivan\n* [[Kunka Baeva]] - Ana\n* [[Borislav Ivanov (actor)|Borislav Ivanov]] - Bazuneka\n* [[Nikolay Doychev]] - Ilcho\n* [[Lyubomir Bobchevski]]\n* [[Naicho Petrov]]\n* [[Hristo Dinev]]\n* [[Stefan Kuyumdzhiev]]\n* [[Dimitar Peshev]]\n* [[Mara Andonova]]\n* [[Nikola Dadov]]\n* [[Teofan Chranov]]\n* [[Trifon Dzhonev]]\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*{{imdb title|id=0279526|title=Earth}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Earth}}\n[[Category:1957 films]]\n[[Category:Bulgarian films]]\n[[Category:Bulgarian-language films]]\n[[Category:1957 drama films]]\n[[Category:Bulgarian black-and-white films]]\n[[Category:Films directed by Zahari Zhandov]]\n[[Category:Bulgarian drama films]]\n{{Bulgaria-film-stub}}\n", "