{"title_page": "John Ferdinand Smyth Stuart", "text_new": "'''John Ferdinand Smyth Stuart''' (1745 \u2013 20 December 1814), was a Scottish-born American loyalist and physician and author of ''A Tour in the United States of America'' (1786) and other works.\n\n==Life==\nStuart was born in Scotland in 1745 and began life there as John Ferdinand Smyth. He was the son of Wentworth Smyth, a Jacobite who had fought in the risings of [[Jacobite rising of 1715|1715]] and [[Jacobite rising of 1745|1745]] and was killed in the Highlands at some time after the birth of his son. According to Stuart\u2019s later account, in 1744 his father was sixty-six and married Maria Julia Dalziel, a girl of fifteen, who died three years later. He reported that his mother was a grand-daughter of [[James Crofts (British Army officer)|General James Crofts]], natural son of the [[James Scott, 1st Duke of Monmouth|Duke of Monmouth]], who was also his father\u2019s grandfather.<ref name=dnb>Edward Irving Carlyle, \u201cStuart, John Ferdinand Smyth\u201d, in ''[[Dictionary of National Biography]] 1885-1900'', Vol. 55</ref>\n\nJohn Ferdinand Smyth studied medicine at the  University of Edinburgh. He then emigrated to North America, and settled near [[Williamsburg, Virginia|Williamsburg]] in the [[Colony of Virginia]], where he practised as a physician. The [[American Revolutionary War|War of Independence]] broke out, and on 15 October 1775, as a loyalist to the Crown, Smyth quitted Virginia and joined the [[British Army]]. He served in several regiments in the rank of captain. At one time he commanded an armed sloop in [[Chesapeake Bay]] and at another raised a company of men for frontier work. More than once he was taken prisoner, and was shackled for eighteen months.<ref name=dnb/> \n\nAt the end of the war, in 1783, Smyth (as he then was) arrived in England and was awarded a pension of \u00a3300 a year. However, in 1784, allegations were made against him to the claims commissioners, and this pension was suspended, never to be reinstated. Impoverished, he took a job as a barrack-master and wrote his book ''A Tour in the United States of America'', which was published by [[George Robinson (1737\u20131801)|George Robinson]] in 1786. In 1793 he adopted the name of Stuart and went on arguing his case to the government, without success.<ref name=dnb/>\n\nIn 1795, Stuart joined [[Admiral (Royal Navy)|Admiral]] [[Hugh Cloberry Christian|Sir Hugh Cloberry Christian]] on an expedition to the [[West Indies]], where he was shipwrecked three times and fought at the British capture of [[Saint Lucia]]. On his return to England, he learned that his financial claims were too old to succeed.<ref name=dnb/> \n\nStuart continued to write. On 7 September 1803, he married Eunice Gray, at [[St Martin-in-the-Fields]], Westminster,<ref>\u201cJohn Ferdinand Dalziel Smyth Stuart and Eunice Gray, Marriage07/09/1803 Saint Martin in the  Fields, Westminster, London\u201c at ancestry.co.uk, accessed 21 April 2020 {{subscription}}</ref> and had two sons and a daughter. On 20 December 1814, he was run over and killed by a carriage which hit him in London at the corner of [[Southampton Street, London|Southampton Street]], leaving his family destitute.<ref>[[Notes and Queries]], 2nd series, VIII, p. 495, IX, pp. 232, 334</ref> He was buried on 1 January 1815 at [[Marylebone]], where the parish register notes that he was of St George\u2019s, Bloomsbury.<ref>''Burials in the Parish of St Mary-le-Bone'',  [https://www.ancestry.co.uk/interactive/1559/31280_194703-00275 p. 2] at ancestry.co.uk, accessed 21 April 2020 {{subscription}}</ref>\n\n==Published works==\nStuart\u2019s book ''A Tour in the United States of America'' (1784) describes his travels there and his activities during the War of Independence.<ref name=dnb/> His view of the country has been called \n{{Quote|\u201c...vigorous but not flattering. The republican opinions of the colonists were obnoxious to a loyalist, while their barbarous manners were repellent to a gentleman.\u201d<ref name=dnb/>}}\n\nHis book ''A Letter to Lord Henry Petty on Coercive Vaccination'' (1807) is a forceful medical and political argument against [[vaccination]] addressed to [[Henry Petty-Fitzmaurice, 3rd Marquess of Lansdowne|Lord Henry Petty]], the youthful [[Chancellor of the Exchequer]].<ref>Chambers, Book of Days, vol. I, p. 628</ref>\n\n''The Case of Ferdinand Smyth Stuart'' (1807) returned to Stuart\u2019s complaints about his treatment by the British government. In his ''Destiny and Fortitude: an heroic poem on the Misfortunes of the House of Stuart'' (1808), he returned to his father\u2019s [[Jacobitism]].<ref name=dnb/>\n\n==Notes==\n{{reflist}}\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Stuart, John Ferdinand Smyth}}\n[[Category:1745 births]]\n[[Category:1814 deaths]]\n[[Category:Alumni of the University of Edinburgh]]\n", "text_old": "'''John Ferdinand Smyth Stuart''' (1745 \u2013 20 December 1814), was a Scottish-born American loyalist and physician and author of ''A Tour in the United States of America'' (1786) and other works.\n\n==Life==\nStuart was born in Scotland in 1745 and began life there as John Ferdinand Smyth. He was the son of Wentworth Smyth, a Jacobite who had fought in the risings of [[Jacobite rising of 1715|1715]] and [[Jacobite rising of 1745|1745]] and was killed in the Highlands at some time after the birth of his son. According to Stuart\u2019s later account, in 1744 his father was sixty-six and married Maria Julia Dalziel, a girl of fifteen, who died three years later. He reported that his mother was a grand-daughter of [[James Crofts (British Army officer)|General James Crofts]], natural son of the [[James Scott, 1st Duke of Monmouth|Duke of Monmouth]], who was also his father\u2019s grandfather.<ref name=dnb>Edward Irving Carlyle, \u201cStuart, John Ferdinand Smyth\u201d, in ''[[Dictionary of National Biography]] 1885-1900'', Vol. 55</ref>\n\nJohn Ferdinand Smyth studied medicine at the  University of Edinburgh. He then emigrated to North America, and settled near [[Williamsburg, Virginia|Williamsburg]] in the [[Colony of Virginia]], where he practised as a physician. The [[American Revolutionary War|War of Independence]] broke out, and on 15 October 1775, as a loyalist to the Crown, Smyth quitted Virginia and joined the [[British Army]]. He served in several regiments in the rank of captain. At one time he commanded an armed sloop in [[Chesapeake Bay]] and at another raised a company of men for frontier work. More than once he was taken prisoner, and was shackled for eighteen months.<ref name=dnb/> \n\nAt the end of the war, in 1783, Smyth (as he then was) arrived in England and was awarded a pension of \u00a3300 a year. However, in 1784, allegations were made against him to the claims commissioners, and this pension was suspended, never to be reinstated. Impoverished, he took a job as a barrack-master and wrote his book ''A Tour in the United States of America'', which was published by [[George Robinson (1737\u20131801)|George Robinson]] in 1786. In 1793 he adopted the name of Stuart and went on arguing his case to the government, without success.<ref name=dnb/>\n\nIn 1795, Stuart joined [[Admiral (Royal Navy)|Admiral]] [[Hugh Cloberry Christian|Sir Hugh Cloberry Christian]] on an expedition to the [[West Indies]], where he was shipwrecked three times and fought at the British capture of [[Saint Lucia]]. On his return to England, he learned that his financial claims were too old to succeed.<ref name=dnb/> \n\nStuart continued to write. On 7 September 1803, he married Eunice Gray, at [[St Martin-in-the-Fields]], Westminster,<ref>\u201cJohn Ferdinand Dalziel Smyth Stuart and Eunice Gray, Marriage07/09/1803 Saint Martin in the  Fields, Westminster, London\u201c at ancestry.co.uk, accessed 21 April 2020 {{subscription}}</ref> and had two sons and a daughter. On 20 December 1814, he was run over and killed by a carriage which hit him in London at the corner of [[Southampton Street]], leaving his family destitute.<ref>[[Notes and Queries]], 2nd series, VIII, p. 495, IX, pp. 232, 334</ref> He was buried on 1 January 1815 at [[Marylebone]], where the parish register notes that he was of St George\u2019s, Bloomsbury.<ref>''Burials in the Parish of St Mary-le-Bone'',  [https://www.ancestry.co.uk/interactive/1559/31280_194703-00275 p. 2] at ancestry.co.uk, accessed 21 April 2020 {{subscription}}</ref>\n\n==Published works==\nStuart\u2019s book ''A Tour in the United States of America'' (1784) describes his travels there and his activities during the War of Independence.<ref name=dnb/> His view of the country has been called \n{{Quote|\u201c...vigorous but not flattering. The republican opinions of the colonists were obnoxious to a loyalist, while their barbarous manners were repellent to a gentleman.\u201d<ref name=dnb/>}}\n\nHis book ''A Letter to Lord Henry Petty on Coercive Vaccination'' (1807) is a forceful medical and political argument against [[vaccination]] addressed to [[Henry Petty-Fitzmaurice, 3rd Marquess of Lansdowne|Lord Henry Petty]], the youthful [[Chancellor of the Exchequer]].<ref>Chambers, Book of Days, vol. I, p. 628</ref>\n\n''The Case of Ferdinand Smyth Stuart'' (1807) returned to Stuart\u2019s complaints about his treatment by the British government. In his ''Destiny and Fortitude: an heroic poem on the Misfortunes of the House of Stuart'' (1808), he returned to his father\u2019s [[Jacobitism]].<ref name=dnb/>\n\n==Notes==\n{{reflist}}\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Stuart, John Ferdinand Smyth}}\n[[Category:1745 births]]\n[[Category:1814 deaths]]\n[[Category:Alumni of the University of Edinburgh]]\n", "name_user": "Moonraker", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eLife", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/John_Ferdinand_Smyth_Stuart"}
